 Force]]<br />[[Operation Uphold Democracy]]<br />[[Operation Desert Spring]]<br />[[Iraq War]]<br />[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n|mawards      = [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (4)<br />[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (3)<br />[[Defense Superior Service Medal]] (2)<br />[[Legion of Merit]] (4)<br />[[Bronze Star Medal]] with [[\"V\" Device|Valor]]<br />[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]<br />[[NATO Medal|NATO Meritorious Service Medal]]<br />[[Officer of the Order of Australia]]<br />[[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]]<br />''([[#Decorations and badges|More]])''\n}}\n'''David Howell Petraeus''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AOh}}, {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MSC}}<ref>http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2011/2011-08-13/pdf/g1-14533.pdf</ref> ({{IPAc-en|p|\u1d7b|\u02c8|t|r|e\u026a|.|\u0259|s}}; born November 7, 1952) is a retired [[United States Army]] [[General (United States)|general]] and public official. He served as [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] from September 6, 2011,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/us/2011/09/06/petraeus-sworn-into-cia.cnn?iref=allsearch |title=Petraeus sworn in as CIA director |publisher=CNN |accessdate=September 7, 2011}}</ref> until his resignation on November 9, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2012/11/09/david-petraeus-cia-resign-nbc/1695271/ |title=David Petraeus resigns from CIA |work=USA Today |accessdate=November 9, 2012 |first1=Kevin |last1=Johnson |date=November 9, 2012}}</ref> Prior to his assuming the directorship of the CIA, Petraeus served 37 years in the [[United States Army]]. His last assignments in the Army were as commander of the [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF) and\nCommander, U.S. Forces \u2013 Afghanistan (USFOR-A) from July 4, 2010, to July 18, 2011. His other [[4 star rank|four-star]] assignments include serving as the 10th Commander, [[United States Central Command|U.S. Central Command]] (USCENTCOM) from October 13, 2008, to June 30, 2010, and as Commanding General, [[Multinational Force Iraq|Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]] (MNF-I) from February 10, 2007, to September 16, 2008.<ref name=\"Change in command\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=51170 |title=Gates Notes Shift in Mission as Iraq Command Changes Hands |publisher=Defenselink.mil |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> As commander of MNF-I, Petraeus oversaw all coalition forces in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Holusha |title=General Calls Iraq Situation Dire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/23/world/middleeast/23cnd-general.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Gordon |title=Bush to Name a New General to Oversee Iraq |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/05/world/middleeast/05military.html |work=The New York Times |date=January 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus has a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree from the [[United States Military Academy]], from which he graduated in 1974 as a distinguished cadet (top 5% of his class). In his class were three other future four-star generals, [[Martin Dempsey]], [[Walter L. Sharp]] and [[Keith B. Alexander]]. He was the [[George Marshall|General George C. Marshall]] Award winner as the top graduate of the [[U.S. Army Command and General Staff College]] class of 1983.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-petraeusbox9sep09,0,3096741.story?coll=la-headlines-nation |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081201125841/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-petraeusbox9sep09,0,3096741.story?coll=la-headlines-nation |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-01 |title=Profile: Gen. David Petraeus |newspaper=Los Angeles Times}} </ref> He subsequently earned an [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]] in 1985 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] degree in [[international relations]] in 1987 from the [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]] at [[Princeton University]]. He later served as Assistant Professor of International Relations at the [[United States Military Academy]] and also completed a fellowship at [[Georgetown University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/about-cia/leadership/david-h.-petraeus.html |title=David H. Petraeus \u2013 Central Intelligence Agency |publisher=CIA |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019190931/https://www.cia.gov/about-cia/leadership/david-h.-petraeus.html |archivedate=October 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nPetraeus has repeatedly stated that he has no plans to run for elected political office.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/tim_hames/article3345681.ece |work=The Times |location=London |title=McCain and Petraeus the dream ticket |first=Tim |last=Hames |date=February 11, 2008 |accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/06/weekinreview/06myers.html |work=The New York Times |title=Generally Speaking |date=April 6, 2008 |accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"msnbc.msn.com\">{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/22379099 |title=Petraeus says he's not interested in presidency |publisher=NBC News |date=December 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"blogs.usatoday.com\">blogs.usatoday.com/onpolitics/2007/09/petraeus-xxxxxx.html {{Dead link|date=April 2011|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> On June 23, 2010, President [[Barack Obama]] nominated Petraeus to succeed General [[Stanley McChrystal]] as commanding general of the [[International Security Assistance Force]] in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]], technically a step down from his position as Commander of [[United States Central Command]], which oversees the military efforts in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Central Asia, the Arabian Peninsula, and [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/top/all/7076132.html |title=Obama replaces McChrystal with Petraeus |work=Houston Chronicle |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/24/us/politics/24mcchrystal.html |title=Gen. McChrystal Is Relieved of Command |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2010 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |author1=Cooper, Helene |authorlink1=Helene Cooper |author2=Shanker, Thom |author3=Filkins, Dexter |authorlink3=Dexter Filkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Peter Grier |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2010/0623/Gen.-David-Petraeus-takes-over-in-Afghanistan-Will-it-make-a-difference |title=Gen. David Petraeus takes over in Afghanistan: Will it make a difference? |work=The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2011, Petraeus was unanimously confirmed as the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|Director of the CIA]] by the U.S. Senate 94\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-petraeus-confirmed-20110630,0,6226030.story |title=Senate confirms David Petraeus as CIA director |date=June 30, 2011 |author=Kathleen Hennessey |newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 30, 2011 }}</ref> Petraeus relinquished command of U.S. and NATO forces in Afghanistan on July 18, 2011, and retired from the U.S. Army on August 31, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=64540 |title=Petraeus Confirmed as CIA Director |date=July 1, 2011 |author=Karen Parrish |agency=American Forces Press Service |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=July 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121144337/http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=64540 |archivedate=January 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On November 9, 2012, he resigned from his position as Director of the CIA, citing his extramarital affair with his biographer [[Paula Broadwell]], which was reportedly discovered in the course of an FBI investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/jill-kelley-e-mails-depict-a-striving-tampa-socialite-and-a-smitten-military-brass/2015/02/03/ef8cb06c-a800-11e4-a06b-9df2002b86a0_story.html|title=In e-mails, glimpses of a striving Tampa socialite and smitten military brass at U.S. Central Command|first=Craig|last=Whitlock|date=February 3, 2015|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2012/11/09/david-petraeus-cia-resign-nbc/1695271/ |title=NBC: David Petraeus resigns from CIA |date=November 9, 2012 |accessdate=November 9, 2012 |work=USA Today |first1=Kevin |last1=Johnson}}</ref> In January 2015, officials reported the FBI and Justice Department prosecutors had recommended bringing felony charges against Petraeus for allegedly providing classified information to Broadwell while serving as Director of the CIA.<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news |last1=Schmidt |first1=Michael |last2=Apuzzo|first2=Matt|authorlink2=Matt Apuzzo|title=F.B.I. and Justice Dept. Said to Seek Charges for Petraeus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/10/us/politics/prosecutors-said-to-recommend-charges-against-former-gen-david-petraeus.html |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Eventually, Petraeus pleaded guilty to one misdemeanor charge of mishandling classified information.<ref name=\"Mar 3 2015\">{{cite news |author= Pierre Thomas |author2=Mike Levine |author3=Jack Cloherty |author4=Jack Date |date=March 3, 2015 |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/cia-head-david-petraeus-plead-guilty/story?id=29340487|title=Former CIA Head David Petraeus to Plead Guilty |publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nPetraeus was born in [[Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York]], the son of Miriam Sweet (n\u00e9e Howell; 1912\u20131991),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Miriam-Sweet-Howell/6000000015418136163|title=Miriam Sweet Howell|publisher=geni.com}}</ref> a librarian, and Sixtus Petraeus (1915\u20132008),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Sixtus-Petraeus/6000000015418360012|title=Sixtus Petraeus|publisher=geni.com}}</ref> a [[Dutch people|Dutch]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2668/Buitenland/article/detail/3346555/2012/11/12/37-jarige-familievriendin-ontving-intimiderende-mails-minnares-Petraeus.dhtml|title=37-jarige 'familievriendin' ontving intimiderende mails minnares Petraeus |author=Editorial |work=De Volkskrant}}</ref> sea captain from [[Franeker]], [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2010/05/petraeus-exclusive-201005 |title=David Petraeus' Winning Streak |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 30, 2010 |accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> His mother was American, a resident of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=\"wapo4\" /> His father had sailed to the United States from the Netherlands at the start of [[World War II]].<ref name=obit1>{{cite web|title=General David Petraeus' Father Dies In Santa Clarita Home|url=http://hometownstation.com/node/13195:david-petraeus-santa-clarita-2008-06-20-20-33&catid=26:local-news&Itemid=97&date=2010-07-01|publisher=KHTS Radio|accessdate=November 18, 2012|author=Carol Rock|date=June 21, 2008}}</ref> They met at the [[Seamen's Church Institute of New York and New Jersey]] and married. Sixtus Petraeus commanded a [[Liberty ship]] for the US for the duration of World War II.<ref name=\"wapo4\">{{cite news|title=Unexpected Challenges Tested Petraeus in Iraq|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A36843-2004Mar6|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110718192208/http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A36843-2004Mar6?language=printer|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 18, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 7, 2004|author=Rick Atkinson|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The family moved after the war, settling in Cornwall-on-Hudson, where David Petraeus grew up and graduated from [[Cornwall Central High School]] in 1970.\n[[File:David and Stephen Petraeus in Afghanistan.jpg|left|thumb|With his son Stephen, [[Afghanistan]], 2010]]\nPetraeus went on to the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point, New York|West Point]]. Petraeus was on the intercollegiate soccer and ski teams, was a cadet captain on the brigade staff, and was a \"distinguished cadet\" academically, graduating in the top 5% of the Class of 1974 (ranked 40th overall). In the class yearbook, Petraeus was remembered as \"always going for it in sports, academics, leadership, and even his social life\".<ref name=\"early bio\">Bruno, Greg; January 11, 2007; [http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070111/NEWS/701110319/-1/NEWS14 New Iraq commander is Cornwall's favorite son]; ''[[Times-Herald Record]]''. Retrieved January 13, 2007.</ref>\n\nWhile a cadet, Petraeus started dating the daughter of Army General [[William A. Knowlton]] (the West Point superintendent at the time), Hollister \"Holly\" Knowlton (born c. 1953).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.time.com/2012/11/14/the-rise-and-fall-of-general-peaches/|title=The Rise and Fall of 'General Peaches' |work=Time}}</ref> Two months after Petraeus graduated, they married.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/12/archives/hollister-knowlton-betrothed-to-david-h-petraeus-a-cadet.html |title=Hollister Knowlton Betrothed To David H. Petraeus, a Cadet |work=The New York Times |date=May 12, 1974 |page=GN57}}</ref> Holly, who is multi-lingual, was a [[National Merit Scholarship Program|National Merit Scholar]] in high school, and graduated ''[[summa cum laude]]'' from [[Dickinson College]]. They have a daughter and son, Anne and Stephen. Petraeus administered the [[United States Uniformed Services Oath of Office|oath of office]] at his son's 2009 commissioning into the Army after his son's graduation from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alum.mit.edu/news/AlumniNews/Archive/petraeus |title=General Petraeus Inducts ROTC Graduates |date=June 11, 2009 |accessdate=June 3, 2010 |publisher=MIT Alumni Association |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609153306/http://alum.mit.edu/news/AlumniNews/Archive/petraeus |archive-date=June 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://alum.mit.edu/sliceofmit/2009/06/06/gen-petraeus-commissions/ |title=Gen. Petraeus Commissions His Son and 11 Other '09 Graduates |date=June 6, 2009 |publisher=MIT Alumni Association |access-date=June 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603223140/http://alum.mit.edu/sliceofmit/2009/06/06/gen-petraeus-commissions/ |archive-date=June 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His son went on to serve as an officer in [[Afghanistan]] as a member of 3rd Platoon, Alpha Company, 1st Battalion, [[503rd Infantry Regiment]], [[173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/03/ap-petraeus-reveals-that-son-served-in-afghanistan-031611/ |title=Petraeus reveals that son served in Afghanistan \u2013 Army News &#124; News from Afghanistan & Iraq |work=Army Times |accessdate=November 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus's official residence in the United States is a small property in the small town of [[Springfield, New Hampshire]], which his wife inherited from her family.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20081007/NEWS/810070403 |title=Gen. Petraeus owns property in New Hampshire |date=October 7, 2008 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Portsmouth Herald]] |location=Portsmouth, New Hampshire}}</ref> Petraeus once told a friend that he was a [[Rockefeller Republican]].<ref name=\"newyorker.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/09/08/the-generals-dilemma |work=The New Yorker |title=The General's Dilemma |date=September 8, 2008 |quote=Petraeus is registered to vote as a Republican in New Hampshire\u2014he once described himself to a friend as a northeastern Republican, in the tradition of Nelson Rockefeller\u2014but he said that around 2002, after he became a two-star general, he stopped voting.}}</ref>\n\n==Education and academia==\nPetraeus graduated from [[West Point]] in 1974. He earned the General [[George C. Marshall]] Award as the top graduate of the [[Command and General Staff College|U.S. Army Command and General Staff College]] Class of 1983 at [[Fort Leavenworth]], [[Kansas]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Military Science]]. He subsequently earned an [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]] in 1985 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[international relations]] in 1987 from [[Princeton University]]'s [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]], where he was mentored by Richard H. Ullman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/main/news/archive/S39/47/30G63/index.xml?section=topstories|title=Princeton University - Diplomatic historian and foreign policy scholar Richard Ullman dies|publisher=Princeton University }}</ref> At that time, he also served as an Assistant Professor of International Relations at the [[United States Military Academy|U.S. Military Academy]] from 1985 to 1987. His doctoral dissertation was titled \"The American Military and the Lessons of [[Vietnam]]: A Study of Military Influence and the Use of Force in the Post-Vietnam Era\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Petraeus |first=David H. |title=The American military and the lessons of Vietnam: A Study of Military Influence and the Use of Force in the Post-Vietnam Era |location=[[Princeton, N.J.]] |publisher=[[Princeton University]] |year=1987 |oclc=20673428}}</ref> He also completed a military fellowship at [[Georgetown University]]'s [[Edmund A. Walsh School of Foreign Service]] in 1994\u20131995,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jaffe |first1=Greg |last2=Cloud |first2=David |date=2009 |title=The Fourth Star: Four Generals and the Epic Struggle for the Future of the United States Army |url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_b2o5 |url-access=registration |quote=petraeus georgetown fellowship 1995. |location=New York |publisher=Crown Publishing |page=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_b2o5/page/97 97] |isbn=978-0-307-40907-2}}</ref> although he was called away early to serve in Haiti as the Chief of Operations for NATO there in early 1995.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nFrom late 2005 through February 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armyupress.army.mil/Journals/Military-Review/Online-Exclusive/2016-Online-Exclusive-Articles/Strategic-Command-General-David-Petraeus/|title=Strategic Command: General David Petraeus|website=www.armyupress.army.mil|first=William J.|last=Denn|date=October 7, 2016}}</ref> Petraeus served as Commanding General of [[Fort Leavenworth]], Kansas, and the [[U.S. Army Combined Arms Center]] (CAC) located there. As commander of CAC, Petraeus was responsible for oversight of the [[Command and General Staff College]] and seventeen other schools, centers, and training programs as well as for developing the Army's doctrinal manuals, training the Army's officers, and supervising the Army's center for the collection and dissemination of lessons learned. During his time at CAC, Petraeus and Marine [[James Mattis|Lt. Gen. James N. Mattis]] jointly oversaw the publication of [[U.S. Army Field Manuals|Field Manual]] 3\u201324, ''Counterinsurgency'', the body of which was written by an extraordinarily diverse group of military officers, academics, human rights advocates, and journalists who had been assembled by Petraeus and Mattis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usacac.leavenworth.army.mil/cac2/coin/repository/FM_3-24.pdf |title=FM 3\u201324 text \u2013 COUNTERINSURGENCY -DECEMBER 2006 |publisher=Usacac.army.mil |date=August 31, 2009 |accessdate=May 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928152550/http://usacac.leavenworth.army.mil/cac2/coin/repository/FM_3-24.pdf |archivedate=September 28, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>Nutt, Cullen; March 2, 2008; ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'' Section 2-page 1 and 4.</ref> Additionally, at both Fort Leavenworth and throughout the military's schools and training programs, Petraeus integrated the study of counterinsurgency into lesson plans and training exercises. In recognition of the fact that soldiers in Iraq often performed duties far different from those for which they trained, Petraeus also stressed the importance of teaching soldiers how to think as well as how to fight, and the need to foster flexibility and adaptability in leaders.<ref>Ricks, Thomas ''[[Fiasco (book)|Fiasco]]'' New York: Penguin Press, 2006, page 419.</ref><ref>Barnes, Julian E.; October 31, 2005; [https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus.htm \"An Open Mind for a New Army\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811130943/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus.htm |date=August 11, 2010 }}; ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''. Retrieved April 2, 2008.</ref> Petraeus called this change the most significant part of [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|The Surge]], saying in 2016 \"the surge that mattered most was the surge of ideas. It was the change of strategy, and in many respects, this represented quite a significant change to what it was we were doing prior to the surge.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conversationswithbillkristol.org/video/david-petraeus/|title=General David Petraeus Reflects on His Command in Iraq|website=Conversations with Bill Kristol}}</ref> Petraeus has been called \"the world's leading expert in counter-insurgency warfare\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/12700/Michael-Gove-Triumph-of-freedom.4812256.jp |title=Michael Gove: Triumph of freedom over evil |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> Later, having refined his ideas on counterinsurgency based on the implementation of the new [[counterinsurgency]] doctrine in Iraq, he published both in Iraq as well as in the Sep/Oct 2008 edition of ''[[Military Review]]'' his \"Commander's Counterinsurgency Guidance\" to help guide leaders and units in the Multi-National Force-Iraq.<ref>Petraeus, D. (September\u2013October 2008) [http://usacac.army.mil/CAC2/MilitaryReview/Archives/English/MilitaryReview_20081031_art004.pdf Multi-national Force-Iraq Commander's Counterinsurgency Guidance]. ''Military Review'' English Edition. Retrieved May 17, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Military operations==\n[[File:GEN Petraeus Aug 2011 Photo.jpg|right|thumb|U.S. Army Gen. David H. Petraeus, during his time in the Army]]\n\n===1970s===\nUpon his graduation from West Point in 1974, Petraeus was commissioned an infantry officer. After completing [[Ranger School]] (Distinguished Honor Graduate and other honors), Petraeus was assigned to the [[509th Infantry Regiment (United States)|509th Airborne Battalion Combat Team]], a light infantry unit stationed in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref>[[Fred Kaplan (journalist)|Fred Kaplan]], \"The Insurgents: David Petraeus and the Plot to Change the American Way of War\", [[Simon & Schuster]], 2013, pages 14-20.</ref> Ever since, [[light infantry]] has been at the core of his career, punctuated by assignments to [[Armoured warfare|mechanized units]], unit commands, staff assignments, and educational institutions. After leaving the 509th as a [[US First Lieutenant|first lieutenant]],<ref>Gal Perl Finkel, [http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/How-to-win-a-modern-war-467149 \"How to win a modern war\"], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', September 7, 2016.</ref> Petraeus began a brief association with mechanized units when he became assistant operations officer on the staff of the 2nd Brigade, [[24th Infantry Division (United States)|24th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]] at [[Fort Stewart]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. In 1979, he assumed command of a [[Company (military unit)|company]] in the same division: A Company, 2nd Battalion, 19th Infantry Regiment (Mechanized), and then served as that battalion's operations officer, a major's position that he held as a junior captain.\n\n===1980s===\nIn 1981, Petraeus became [[aide-de-camp]] to General John Galvin, then Commanding General of the [[24th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]].<ref name=\"NPR_20070123\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6952481 |title=Petraeus Set for Another Shot at Iraq |publisher=NPR |date = January 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> He spent the next few years furthering his military and civilian education, including spending 1982\u201383 at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, attending the Command and General Staff College. At graduation in 1983, he was the General George C. Marshall Award winner as the top graduate of the U.S. Army Command and General Staff College. From 1983 to 1985, he was at Princeton; and 1985\u201387 at West Point. After earning his PhD and teaching at West Point, Petraeus continued up the rungs of the command ladder, serving as military assistant to Gen. [[John Galvin (soldier)|John Galvin]], the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe|Supreme Allied Commander in Europe]]. From there, he moved to the [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Infantry Division (Mechanized)]]. During 1988\u20131989, he served as operations officer to the 3rd Infantry Division (Mechanized)'s [[30th Infantry Regiment (United States)|30th Infantry Regiment]]. He was then posted as aide and assistant executive officer to the U.S. Army Chief of Staff, General [[Carl Vuono]], in Washington, D.C.\n\n===1990s===\nUpon promotion to [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]], Petraeus moved from the office of the Chief of Staff to [[Fort Campbell]], [[Kentucky]], where he commanded the [[101st Airborne Division|101st Airborne Division (Air Assault)]]'s 3rd Battalion [[187th Infantry Regiment (United States)|187th Infantry Regiment]], known as the \"Iron Rakkasans\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/3-187in.htm |title=3rd Battalion, 187th Infantry Regimen |author=John Pike |date=May 7, 2011 |publisher=globalsecurity.org}}</ref> from 1991 to 1993. During this period, he suffered one of the more dramatic incidents in his career; in 1991 he was accidentally shot in the chest with an [[M16 rifle|M-16]] rifle during a [[live-fire exercise]] when a soldier tripped and his rifle discharged.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lasting Ties Mark Gen. Petraeus's Career |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7193883 |date=February 6, 2007 |first=Steve |last=Inskeep |authorlink=Steve Inskeep |publisher=NPR |accessdate=June 22, 2010}}</ref> He was taken to [[Vanderbilt University Medical Center]], [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], where he was operated on by future [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Bill Frist]]. The hospital released him early after he did fifty [[push-up]]s without resting, just a few days after the accident.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Atkinson |title=Iraq Will be Petraeus' Knot to Untie |work=The Washington Post |page=A15 |date=January 7, 2007}}</ref><ref>Atkinson, Rick, ''In the Company of Soldiers: A Chronicle of Combat'' (New York: Henry Holt & Co., 2004, {{ISBN|0-641-78803-7}}), p. 38.</ref>\n\nDuring 1993\u201394, Petraeus continued his long association with the 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault) as the division's Assistant Chief of Staff, G-3 (plans, operations and training) and installation Director of Plans, Training, and Mobilization (DPTM). In 1995, he was assigned to the [[United Nations]] Mission in [[Haiti]] Military Staff as its Chief Operations Officer during [[Operation Uphold Democracy]]. His next command, from 1995 to 1997, was the 1st Brigade, [[82nd Airborne Division]], centered on the [[504th Infantry Regiment (United States)|504th Parachute Infantry Regiment]]. At that post, his brigade's training cycle at [[Fort Polk|Fort Polk's Joint Readiness Training Center]] for low-intensity warfare was chronicled by novelist and military enthusiast [[Tom Clancy]] in his book ''Airborne''. From 1997 to 1999, Petraeus served in [[the Pentagon]] as Executive Assistant to the Director of the Joint Staff and then to the [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff|Chairman of the Joint Chiefs]], Gen. [[Henry Shelton]], who described Petraeus as \"a high-energy individual who likes to lead from the front, in any field he is going into\".<ref>Barnes, Julian [https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus_2.htm \"An Open Mind for a New Army\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206180235/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus_2.htm |date=February 6, 2008 }} May 31, 2005. Retrieved April 2, 2008.</ref> In 1999, as a [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], Petraeus returned to the 82nd, serving as the assistant division commander for operations and then, briefly, as acting commanding general. During his time with the 82nd, he deployed to [[Kuwait]] as part of [[Operation Desert Spring]], the continuous rotation of combat forces through Kuwait during the decade after the [[Gulf War]].\n\n===2000s===\nFrom the 82nd, he moved on to serve as Chief of Staff of [[XVIII Airborne Corps]] at [[Fort Bragg, North Carolina|Fort Bragg]] during 2000\u20132001. In 2000, Petraeus suffered his second major injury, when, during a civilian [[skydiving]] jump, his parachute collapsed at low altitude due to a hook turn, resulting in a hard landing that broke his pelvis. He was selected for promotion to [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=2951 |title=General Officer Announcements |accessdate=October 29, 2007 |date=June 19, 2001 |work=DefenseLink}}</ref> During 2001\u20132002, as a brigadier general, Petraeus served a ten-month tour in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as part of [[Operation Joint Forge]]. In Bosnia, he was the [[NATO]] [[SFOR|Stabilization Force]] Assistant Chief of Staff for Operations as well as the Deputy Commander of the U.S. Joint Interagency Counter-Terrorism Task Force, a command created after the [[September 11 attacks]] to add counterterrorism capability to the U.S. forces attached to the NATO command in Bosnia. In 2004, he was promoted to lieutenant general.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=7342 |title=Army General Officer Announcement |accessdate=October 29, 2007 |date=May 5, 2004 |work=DefenseLink}}</ref> In 2007, he was promoted to General.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=10409 |title=General Officer Announcements |accessdate=October 29, 2007 |date=January 17, 2007 |work=DefenseLink}}</ref> On April 23, 2008, Secretary of Defense Gates announced that President Bush was nominating General Petraeus to command [[U.S. Central Command]] (USCENTCOM), headquartered in [[Tampa]], Florida. In 2010, Petraeus was nominated to command the [[International Security Assistance Force]] in [[Afghanistan]], which required [[List of positions filled by presidential appointment with Senate confirmation|Senate confirmation]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/24/washington/23cnd-petraeus.html |title=2 Commanders Picked to Lead War Efforts Beyond 2008 |accessdate=April 25, 2008 |date=April 24, 2008 |work=The New York Times |first=Thom |last=Shanker}}</ref> He was confirmed on June 30, 2010,<ref name=\"petraeus confirmed IT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0630/breaking54.html|title=Petraeus confirmed as commander |date=June 30, 2010|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=June 30, 2010}}</ref> and took over command from temporary commander [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[Sir Nick Parker]] on July 4, 2010.<ref name=\"assume command\">{{cite news|url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/gen.-petraeus-to-assume-command-of-isaf.html |title=Gen. Petraeus to Assume Command of ISAF |date=July 2, 2010 |work=ISAF Public Affairs Office |accessdate=July 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720194639/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/gen.-petraeus-to-assume-command-of-isaf.html |archivedate=July 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Involvement in the Iraq War===\n\n====101st Airborne Division====\n[[File:Petraeus and Lieutenant General William S. Wallace.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Maj. Gen. David H. Petraeus (right), commanding general, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault), looks on as Lt. Gen. [[William S. Wallace]], V Corps commanding general speaks to soldiers, March 21, 2003, Kuwait.]]\n\nIn 2003, Petraeus, then a major general, saw combat for the first time when he commanded the 101st Airborne Division during [[V Corps (United States)|V Corps's]] drive to [[Baghdad]]. In a campaign chronicled in detail by [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author [[Rick Atkinson]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in the book ''In the Company of Soldiers'', Petraeus led his division through fierce fighting south of [[Baghdad]], in [[Karbala]], [[Al Hillah|Hilla]] and [[Najaf]]. Following the [[2003 invasion of Baghdad|fall of Baghdad]], the division conducted the longest [[Military helicopters|heliborne assault]] on record in order to reach [[Nineveh Governorate]], where it would spend much of 2003. The 1st Brigade was responsible for the area [[Nineveh Governorate|south of Mosul]], the 2nd Brigade for the city itself, and the 3rd Brigade for the region stretching toward the [[Syria]]n border. An often-repeated story of Petraeus's time with the 101st is his asking of [[Embedded journalist|embedded]] ''[[The Washington Post]]'' [[reporter]] [[Rick Atkinson]] to \"Tell me how this ends,\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/04/books/the-story-of-o.html |work=The New York Times |title=The Story of O |first=Christopher |last=Dickey |date=April 4, 2004 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> an anecdote he and other journalists have used to portray Petraeus as an early recognizer of the difficulties that would follow the fall of Baghdad.<ref name=\"NPR_20070123\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/middle_east/article2439520.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |title=US general who acknowledges that the way ahead is not easy |first=Andrew |last=Buncombe |date=April 11, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123032419/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/middle_east/article2439520.ece |archivedate=November 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/06/AR2007010601185.html |work=The Washington Post |title=Iraq Will Be Petraeus' Knot to Untie |first=Rick |last=Atkinson |date=January 7, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Jennifer Hoar |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/03/16/iraq/main2579098.shtml |title=Iraq: Tell Me How This Ends, David Martin: It's Not Worth Arguing About Who Made Mistakes, Just How To End The War |publisher=CBS News |date=March 18, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Hemingway |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/222101/generals-media-playbook/mark-hemingway |title=General's Media Playbook |work=National Review |date=September 10, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/04/15/ING5GP49UK902.DTL |title=Can Petraeus lead U.S. to victory? / General may be military's best \u2013 and last \u2013 hope in Iraq |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=April 15, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |first=Anna |last=Badkhen}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Mosul]], a city of nearly two million people, Petraeus and the 101st employed classic counterinsurgency methods to build security and stability, including conducting targeted kinetic operations and using force judiciously, jump-starting the economy, building local security forces, staging elections for the city council within weeks of their arrival, overseeing a program of [[public works]], reinvigorating the political process,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2004/07/05/iraq-s-repairman.print.html |title=Iraq's Repairman |work=Newsweek |date=July 4, 2004 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksgcase.harvard.edu/casetitle.asp?caseNo=1834.0 |title=CaseWeb: 1834.0 The Accidental Statesman: General Petraeus and the City of Mosul, Iraq |publisher=Harvard Kennedy School |date=October 4, 2006 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>Ricks, Thomas. ''Fiasco'' (New York: Penguin Press, 2006) page 228-232.</ref> and launching 4,500 [[Reconstruction of Iraq|reconstruction projects in Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/beyond/interviews/petraeus.html |title=Frontline: Beyond Baghdad: Interviews: Maj. Gen. David Petraeus |publisher=PBS |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> This approach can be attributed to Petraeus, who had been steeped in nation-building during his previous tours in nations such as Bosnia and Haiti and thus approached nation-building as a central military mission and who was \"prepared to act while the civilian authority in Baghdad was still getting organized\", according to Michael Gordon of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gordon |first=Michael |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/04/world/struggle-for-iraq-reconstruction-101st-airborne-scores-success-northern-iraq.html |title=The Struggle For Iraq: Reconstruction; 101st Airborne Scores Success In Northern Iraq |date=September 4, 2003 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Some Iraqis gave Petraeus the nickname '[[King David]]',<ref name=autogenerated1/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/01/06/wirq106.xml |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |title=Biggest challenge for 'pied piper of N. Iraq' |date=January 6, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2011}}</ref> which was later adopted by some of his colleagues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.military.com/forums/0,15240,126628,00.html |title=Petraeus, Our Old New Man in Iraq |publisher=Military.com |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6730560 |title=Leader of the Fabled 101st to Command in Iraq |publisher=NPR |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Atkinson |first=Rick |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003515887_petraeusprofile09.html |title=New Iraq commander tough and driven |work=The Seattle Times |date=January 9, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524065724/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003515887_petraeusprofile09.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2004, ''[[Newsweek]]'' stated that \"It's widely accepted that no force worked harder to win Iraqi hearts and minds than the 101st Airborne Division led by Petraeus.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/newsweek-cover-can-this-man-save-iraq-75166612.html |title=Newsweek Cover: 'Can This Man Save Iraq?'|date=June 27, 2004 |publisher=PR Newswire |accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:101st Airborne Division - Iraq 01.jpg|thumb|Petraeus on patrol in [[Mosul]] with Gen. [[Peter Schoomaker|Peter J. Schoomaker]], 2003]]\nOne of the General's major [[public works]] was the restoration and re-opening of the [[University of Mosul]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.assistnews.net/ansarticle.asp?URL=Stories/2007/s07090106.htm |title=Welcome support from Petraeus, Crocker for the Assyrian Christians of Iraq |publisher=Assistnews.net |date=September 13, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627020733/http://www.assistnews.net/ansarticle.asp?URL=Stories%2F2007%2Fs07090106.htm |archivedate=June 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Learning Counterinsurgency\">{{cite magazine |author=David Petraeus |url=http://usacac.army.mil/CAC2/MilitaryReview/Archives/English/MilitaryReview_2006CR1031_art010.pdf |title=Learning Counterinsurgency: Observations from Soldiering in Iraq |magazine=Military Review |date=January\u2013February 2006 |pages=45\u201356 |accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> Petraeus strongly supported the use of commanders' discretionary funds for public works, telling [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] [[Civilian Administrator of Iraq|director]] [[L. Paul Bremer]] \"Money is ammunition\" during the director's first visit to [[Mosul]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Dennis Steele |date=November 2003 |magazine=Army |url=http://209.235.252.76/publications/armymagazine/archive/2003/11/Documents/Steele_1103.pdf |title=The race to win the peace |pages=8\u201313 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130035946/http://209.235.252.76/publications/armymagazine/archive/2003/11/Documents/Steele_1103.pdf |archive-date=November 30, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Major Robert S. Widmann USAF |title=The Commander's Emergency Response Program Part II |url=http://www.uscav.com/uscavonpoint/Feature.aspx?id=169 |publisher=U.S. Cavalry |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201174025/http://www.uscav.com/uscavonpoint/Feature.aspx?id=169 |archivedate=December 1, 2008 }}</ref> Petraeus's often repeated<ref>{{cite news |last=Noonan |first=Peggy |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/columnists/pnoonan/?id=110010448 |title='Get It Done' |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 11, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.frontpagemag.com/Articles/Read.aspx?GUID={4E50B495-41D8-4F1E-BDFC-9B24EACA0917} |title=unknown title |publisher=FrontPage Magazine |date=June 26, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921235023/http://www.frontpagemag.com/Articles/Read.aspx?GUID=%7B4E50B495-41D8-4F1E-BDFC-9B24EACA0917%7D |archivedate=September 21, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040113010441/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3771204/|url-status=dead|title=MSN &#124; Outlook, Office, Skype, Bing, Breaking News, and Latest Videos|archivedate=January 13, 2004|website=www.msn.com}}</ref> [[catchphrase]] was later incorporated into official military briefings<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/04/international/worldspecial/04NORT.html |work=The New York Times |title=101st Airborne Scores Success in Reconstruction of Northern Iraq |first=Michael R. |last=Gordon |date=September 4, 2003 |accessdate=May 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usacac.leavenworth.army.mil/CAC/milreview/English/JanFeb06/Petraeus1.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 17, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127032102/http://usacac.leavenworth.army.mil/CAC/milreview/English/JanFeb06/Petraeus1.pdf |archivedate=November 27, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> and was also eventually incorporated into the U.S. Army Counterinsurgency Field Manual drafted with Petraeus's oversight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/841519.html |title=Paradoxes of Counterinsurgency Operations from the U.S. Army/Marine Corps Counterinsurgency Field Manual |publisher=University of Chicago |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PetraeusBSM VDevice.jpg|thumb|Award of the Bronze Star Medal with V Device awarded to Petraeus for actions in combat leading the 101st Airborne (Air Assault) Division during Iraqi Freedom, awarded May 2003.|left|thumb|Petraeus's Bronze Star Medal with V Device for actions in combat leading the 101st Airborne (Air Assault) Division during Operation Iraqi Freedom, May 2003]]\nIn February 2004, the 101st was replaced in Mosul by a portion of I Corps headquarters, but operational forces consisted solely of a unit roughly one quarter its size\u2014a [[Stryker]] brigade. The following summer, the Governor of Nineveh Province was assassinated and most of the Sunni Arab Provincial Council members walked out in the ensuing selection of the new governor, leaving Kurdish members in charge of a predominantly Sunni Arab province. Later that year, the local police commander defected to the Kurdish Minister of Interior in Irbil after repeated assassination attempts against him, attacks on his house, and the kidnapping of his sister. The largely [[Sunni]] [[Arab]] police collapsed under insurgent attacks launched at the same time Coalition Forces attacked [[Fallujah]] in November 2004.\n\n[[File:Petraeus Combat Action Badge Orders.pdf|right|thumb|Orders awarding the Combat Action Badge to then LTG David H. Petraeus for actions in combat during Iraqi Freedom]]\nThere are differing explanations for the apparent collapse of the police force in Mosul. ''[[The Guardian]]'' quoted an anonymous US diplomat saying \"Mosul basically collapsed after he [Petraeus] left.\" Former diplomat [[Peter Galbraith]] criticized Petraeus's command of the 101st, saying his achievements have been exaggerated and his reputation is inflated. He wrote for ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' that \"Petraeus ignored warnings from America's Kurdish allies that he was appointing the wrong people to key positions in Mosul's local government and police.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Peter W. Galbraith |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/19950#fn1 |title=The Surge|work=The New York Review of Books |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> On the other hand, in the book ''Fiasco'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reporter Tom Ricks wrote that \"Mosul was quiet while he (Petraeus) was there, and likely would have remained so had his successor had as many troops as he had\u2014and as much understanding of counterinsurgency techniques.\" Ricks went on to say that \"the population-oriented approach Petraeus took in Mosul in 2003 would be the one the entire U.S. Army in Iraq was trying to adopt in 2006.\"<ref>Fiasco by Thomas Ricks (New York: Penguin Press, 2006) page 232.</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' columnist [[Joe Klein (journalist)|Joe Klein]] largely agreed with Ricks, writing that the [[Stryker]] brigade that replaced the 101st \"didn't do any of the local governance that Petraeus had done\". Moving away from counterinsurgency principles, \"they were occupiers, not builders.\"<ref>Klein, Joe. [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1576838,00.html \"When Bad Missions Happen to Good Generals\"] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' January 22, 2007. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporter Michael Gordon and retired General Bernard Trainor echoed Ricks and Klein, including in their book ''Cobra II'' a quote that Petraeus \"did it right and won over Mosul\".<ref>Gordon, Michael and Bernard Trainor. ''Cobra II'' New York: Panetheon Books, 2006, pages 455\u201356.</ref>\n\n====Multi-National Security Transition Command \u2013 Iraq====\nIn June 2004, less than six months after the 101st returned to the U.S., Petraeus was promoted to lieutenant general and became the first commander of the [[Multi-National Security Transition Command - Iraq]]. This newly created command had responsibility for training, equipping, and mentoring Iraq's growing army, police, and other security forces as well as developing Iraq's security institutions and building associated infrastructure, such as training bases, police stations, and border forts. During Petraeus's fifteen months at the helm of MNSTC-I, he stood up a three-star command virtually from scratch and in the midst of serious fighting in places like Fallujah, Mosul, and Najaf. By the end of his command, some 100,000 Iraqi Security Forces had been trained; Iraqi Army and Police were being employed in combat; countless reconstruction projects had been executed; and hundreds of thousands of weapons, body armor, and other equipment had been distributed in what was described as the \"largest military procurement and distribution effort since World War II\", at a cost of over $11 billion.<ref>Ajami, Faoud. The Foreigner's Gift (New York: Simon and Schuster, 2006) pages 295\u2013298.</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, Petraeus wrote an article for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in which he described the tangible progress being made in building Iraq's security forces from the ground up while also noting the many challenges associated with doing so. \"Although there have been reverses \u2013 not to mention horrific terrorist attacks,\" Petraeus wrote, \"there has been progress in the effort to enable Iraqis to shoulder more of the load for their own security, something they are keen to do.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A49283-2004Sep25.html |title=Battling for Iraq |work=The Washington Post |date=September 26, 2004 |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |first=David H. |last=Petraeus}}</ref> Some of the challenges involved in building security forces had to do with accomplishing this task in the midst of a tough insurgency\u2014or, as Petraeus wrote, \"making the mission akin to repairing an aircraft while in flight \u2013 and while being shot at\". Other challenges included allegations of corruption as well as efforts to improve Iraq's supply accountability procedures. For example, according to former [[Interim Iraq Governing Council]] member [[Ali A. Allawi]] in ''The Occupation of Iraq: Winning the War, Losing the Peace'', \"under the very noses of the security transition command, officials both inside and outside the ministry of defense were planning to embezzle most, if not all, of the procurement budget of the army.\"<ref>{{cite book |url= https://archive.org/details/occupationofiraq00alla |url-access= registration |last=Allawi |first=Ali A. |year=2008 |title=The Occupation of Iraq: Winning the War, Losing the Peace |publisher=Yale University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/occupationofiraq00alla/page/361 361] |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |isbn=978-0-300-11015-9}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' stated in August 2007 that [[the Pentagon]] had lost track of approximately 30% of weapons supplied to the Iraqi security forces. The [[General Accounting Office]] said that the weapons distribution was haphazard, rushed, and did not follow established procedures\u2014particularly from 2004 to 2005, when security training was led by Petraeus and Iraq's security forces began to see combat in places like Najaf and Samarra.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/05/AR2007080501299.html|title=Weapons Given to Iraq Are Missing on August 7, 2007|work=The Washington Post |date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=July 5, 2010|first=Glenn|last=Kessler}}</ref> Over a hundred thousand [[AK-47]] [[assault rifle]]s and [[pistol]]s were delivered to Iraqi forces without full documentation, and some of the missing weapons may have been abducted by [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgents]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/|title=The Daily Beast|website=The Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. shoots self in foot with lost weapons in Iraq |date=August 14, 2007 |newspaper=[[The Oakland Tribune]] |url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2007/08/14/u-s-shoots-self-in-foot-with-lost-weapons-in-iraq/}}</ref> Thousands of [[body armour]] pieces have also been lost.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6932710.stm|title=US 'loses track' of Iraq weapons|work=BBC News|date= August 6, 2007|accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' has stated that the military believed \"the situation on the ground was so urgent, and the agency responsible for recording the transfers of arms so short staffed, that field commanders had little choice in the matter.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article2841342.ece|work=The Independent|location=London|title=Pentagon admits 190,000 weapons missing in Iraq|first=Rupert|last=Cornwell|date=August 7, 2007|accessdate=May 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724114742/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article2841342.ece|archivedate=July 24, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Pentagon conducted its own investigation, and accountability was subsequently regained for many of the weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/05/AR2007080501299_pf.html |work=The Washington Post|title=Weapons Given to Iraq Are Missing|first=Glenn|last=Kessler|accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his second tour in Iraq, Petraeus authored a widely read article in ''Military Review'', listing fourteen observations he had made during two tours in Iraq, including: do not do too much with your own hands, money is ammunition, increasing the number of stakeholders is critical to success, success in a counterinsurgency requires more than just military operations, ultimate success depends on local leaders, there is no substitute for flexible and adaptable leaders, and, finally, a leader's most important task is to set the right tone.<ref>[http://www.au.af.mil/au/awc/awcgate/milreview/petraeus1.pdf \"Learning Counterinsurgency: Observations from Soldiering in Iraq\"] in ''[[Military Review]]''.</ref>\n\n====Multi-National Force&nbsp;\u2013 Iraq (spring 2007)====\n[[File:GEN Petraeus Walking Through Market 11 March 2007 in Baghdad.jpg|thumb|Petraeus walking through a market in Baghdad, March 2007]]\nThe intervening time between the Iraq commands was spent at Fort Leavenworth where the General further developed his military doctrine and pursued an important White House contact in [[Meghan O'Sullivan]] who was the principal adviser to the President on the war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?310883-1/book-discussion-insurgents|title=Book Discussion Insurgents - Video - C-SPAN.org|work=C-SPAN.org}}</ref> In January 2007, as part of his overhauled Iraq strategy, President [[George W. Bush]] announced that Petraeus would succeed Gen. [[George William Casey Jr.|George Casey]] as commanding general of MNF-I to lead all U.S. troops in Iraq. On January 23, the [[Senate Armed Services Committee]] held Petraeus's nomination hearing, during which he testified on his ideas for Iraq, particularly the strategy underpinning the \"[[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|surge]]\" of forces. During his opening statement, Petraeus stated that \"security of the population, especially in Baghdad, and in partnership with the Iraqi Security Forces, will be the focus of the military effort.\" He went on to state that security will require establishing a persistent presence, especially in Iraq's most threatened neighborhoods. He also noted the critical importance of helping Iraq increase its governmental capacity, develop employment programs, and improve daily life for its citizens.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/23/world/middleeast/24petraeustextcnd.html |title=General Petraeus' Opening Statement |work=The New York Times|date=January 23, 2007 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThroughout Petraeus's tenure in Iraq, [[Multi-National Force-Iraq]] endeavored to work with the [[Iraq|Government of Iraq]] to carry out this strategy that focuses on securing the population. Doing so required establishing\u2014and maintaining\u2014persistent presence by living among the population, separating reconcilable Iraqis from irreconcilable enemies, relentlessly pursuing the enemy, taking back sanctuaries and then holding areas that have been cleared, and continuing to develop Iraq's security forces and to support local security forces, often called [[Sons of Iraq]], and to integrate them into the Iraqi Army and Police and other employment programs.<ref>Klein, Joe. [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1638128,00.html \"Operation Last Chance\"] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''June 28, 2007. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>Peters, Ralph. [http://www.nypost.com/seven/08222007/postopinion/opedcolumnists/iraqs_re_liberation.htm \"Iraq's Reliberation\"] ''[[New York Post]]'' August 22, 2007. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>Robinson, Linda. [https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/070520/28petraeus.htm \"Petraeus Tries to Make Headway in Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401011306/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/070520/28petraeus.htm |date=April 1, 2008 }} ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' May 28, 2007. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe strategy underpinning the \"surge\" of forces, as well as the ideas Petraeus included in US army Field Manual 3\u201324, ''Counterinsurgency'', have been referred to by some journalists and politicians as the \"Petraeus Doctrine\", although the surge itself was proposed a few months before Petraeus took command. Despite the misgivings of most Democratic and a few Republican senators over the proposed implementation of the \"Petraeus Doctrine\" in Iraq, specifically regarding the troop surge, Petraeus was unanimously confirmed as a four-star general and MNF-I commander on January 27.<ref>Baker, Peter. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/06/AR2007020601918.html \"General Is Front Man For Bush's Iraq Plan\"], ''The Washington Post'', February 7, 2007. Retrieved February 8, 2007.</ref><ref>Sennott, Charles M. [https://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2007/01/28/the_petraeus_doctrine/?page=3 \"The Petraeus doctrine\"], ''The Boston Globe'', January 28, 2007. Retrieved February 8, 2007.</ref>\n\nBefore leaving for Iraq, Petraeus recruited a number of highly educated military officers, nicknamed \"Petraeus guys\" or \"designated thinkers\", to advise him as commander, including Col. Mike Meese, head of the Social Sciences Department at West Point and Col. [[H.R. McMaster]], famous for his leadership at the [[Battle of 73 Easting]] in the Gulf War and in the pacification of [[Tal Afar]] more recently, as well as for his doctoral dissertation on Vietnam-era civil-military relations titled [[Dereliction of Duty (1998 book)|''Dereliction of Duty'']]. While most of Petraeus's closest advisers are American military officers, he also hired Lt. Col. [[David Kilcullen]] of the [[Australian Army]], who was working for the [[US State Department]].<ref>Ricks, Thomas E. [https://www.nbcnews.com/id/16979340 \"Petraeus selects team of warrior-intellectuals\"], NBC News, February 5, 2007. Retrieved February 7, 2007.</ref> Kilcullen upon his return from Iraq published ''The Accidental Guerrilla'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Jung|first=Alex|url=http://www.salon.com/books/review/2009/03/11/kilcullen/|title=Meet the accidental guerrillas \u2013 Laura Miller|work=Salon|date=March 11, 2009|accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> and has discussed the central front of the war and lessons learned in Iraq in ''The Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/19/AR2009031903038.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Carlos|last=Lozada|accessdate=March 31, 2010|title=A Conversation With David Kilcullen|date=March 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David H. Petraeus press briefing 2007.jpg|right|thumb|U.S. Army Gen. David H. Petraeus, the commander of [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]], briefs reporters at the Pentagon April 26, 2007, on his view of the current military situation in Iraq.]]\n\nAfter taking command of MNF-I on February 10, 2007, Petraeus inspected U.S. and Iraqi units all over Iraq, visiting outposts in greater [[Baghdad]], [[Tikrit]], [[Baqubah|Baquba]], [[Ramadi]], [[Mosul]], [[Kirkuk]], [[Bayji]], [[Samarra]], [[Basrah]] and as far west as al-Hit and Al Qaim. In April 2007, Petraeus made his first visit to Washington as MNF-I Commander, reporting to President Bush and Congress on the progress of the \"surge\" and the overall situation in Iraq. During this visit he met privately with members of Congress and reportedly argued against setting a timetable for U.S. troop withdrawal from Iraq.<ref name=\"CNN Senate Iraq\">{{cite news|title=Senate passes Iraq withdrawal bill; veto threat looms|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/POLITICS/04/26/congress.iraq/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=April 26, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBy late May 2007, Congress did not impose any timetables in war funding legislation for troop withdrawal.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.finalcall.com/artman/publish/article_3575.shtml|title=Congress surrenders to Bush, ''FinalCall''|newspaper= Final Call |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> The enacted legislation did mandate that Petraeus and U.S. Ambassador to Iraq, [[Ryan Crocker]], deliver a report to Congress by September 15, 2007, detailing their assessment of the military, economic and political situation of Iraq.\n\nIn June 2007, Petraeus stated in an interview that there were \"astonishing signs of normalcy\" in Baghdad, and this comment drew criticism from Senate majority leader [[Harry Reid]]. In the same interview, however, Petraeus stated that \"many problems remain\" and he noted the need to help the Iraqis \"stitch back together the fabric of society that was torn during the height of sectarian violence\" in late 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capitolhillblue.com/cont/node/2717|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927225421/http://www.capitolhillblue.com/cont/node/2717|url-status=dead|title=Reid Blasts Generals on Iraq (June 15, 2007), ''Capital Hill Blue''|archivedate=September 27, 2007}}</ref> Petraeus also warned that he expected that the situation in Iraq would require the continued deployment of the elevated troop level of more than 150,000 beyond September 2007; he also stated that U.S. involvement in Iraq could last years afterward.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/17/AR2007061700830.html|title=Petraeus: Iraq 'Challenges' to Last for Years|date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=July 5, 2010|first=Karen |last=DeYoung|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> These statements are representative of the fact that throughout their time in Iraq, Petraeus and Crocker remained circumspect and refused to classify themselves as optimists or pessimists, noting, instead, that they were realists and that the reality in Iraq was very hard. They also repeatedly emphasized the importance of forthright reports and an unvarnished approach.<ref>Burns, John F. [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/14/world/middleeast/14petraeus.html \"For Top General in Iraq, Role is a Mixed Blessing\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'' August 18, 2007. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7155628.stm |title=Petraeus lauds Iraq violence fall |work=BBC News |date=December 21, 2007 |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Indeed, Petraeus's realistic approach and assessments were lauded during the McLaughlin Group's 2008 Year-End Awards, when [[Monica Crowley]] nominated Petraeus for the most honest person of the year, stating, \"...{{nbsp}}[H]e spoke about the great successes of the surge in Iraq, but he always tempered it, never sugar-coated it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mclaughlin.com/library/transcript.htm?id=699|title= The McLaughlin Group|publisher= Mclaughlin.com|accessdate= July 4, 2010|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110613073011/http://www.mclaughlin.com/library/transcript.htm?id=699|archivedate= June 13, 2011|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Multi-National Force&nbsp;\u2013 Iraq (summer and fall 2007)====\nIn July 2007, the [[White House]] submitted to Congress the [[Initial Benchmark Assessment Report|interim report on Iraq]], which stated that coalition forces had made satisfactory progress on 6 of 18 benchmarks set by Congress. On September 7, 2007, in a letter addressed to the troops he was commanding, Petraeus wrote that much military progress had been made, but that the national level political progress that was hoped for had not been achieved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/images/stories/CGs_Corner/070907_cg_mess.pdf |title=The Official Web Site &#124; United States Forces \u2013 Iraq |publisher=Mnf-iraq.com |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809082246/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/images/stories/CGs_Corner/070907_cg_mess.pdf |archivedate=August 9, 2009 }}</ref> Petraeus's [[Report to Congress on the Situation in Iraq]] was delivered to Congress on September 10, 2007.\n\nOn August 15, 2007, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated that, according to [[Journalism sourcing|unnamed administration officials]], the report \"would actually be written by the [[George W. Bush Administration|White House]], with inputs from officials throughout the government\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/print/2007/aug/15/world/fg-pullback15 |title=Top general may propose pullbacks |work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 15, 2007 |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |first1=Julian E. |last1=Barnes |first2=Peter |last2=Spiegel}}</ref> However, Petraeus declared in his testimony to Congress that \"I wrote this testimony myself.\" He further elaborated that his testimony to Congress \"has not been cleared by, nor shared with, anyone in the Pentagon, the White House, or Congress\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/|title=U.S. Department of Defense|website=U.S. Department of Defense}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bush-anbar.jpg|thumb|GEN Petraeus with LTG [[Raymond Odierno|Odierno]] (left), President [[George W. Bush|Bush]] (center), SecDef [[Robert Gates|Gates]], and SecState [[Condoleezza Rice|Rice]] (right) at [[Al Asad Airbase]] in September 2007]]\nIn his September Congressional testimony, Petraeus stated that \"As a bottom line up front, the military objectives of the surge are, in large measure, being met.\" He cited numerous factors for this progress, to include the fact that Coalition and Iraqi Forces had dealt significant blows to Al-Qaeda Iraq and had disrupted Shia militias, that ethno-sectarian violence had been reduced, and that the tribal rejection of Al-Qaeda had spread from Anbar Province to numerous other locations across Iraq. Based on this progress and additional progress expected to be achieved, Petraeus recommended drawing down the surge forces from Iraq and gradually transitioning increased responsibilities to Iraqi Forces, as their capabilities and conditions on the ground permitted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/world/20070911_POLICY/Petraeus_Testimony.pdf |title=Testimony to Congress on the Situation in Iraq |format=PDF |accessdate=October 1, 2011 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n[[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[Harry Reid]] of [[Nevada]] argued Petraeus's \"plan is just more of the same\" and \"is neither a drawdown or a change in mission that we need\". Democratic [[United States House|Representative]] [[Robert Wexler]] of [[Florida]] accused Petraeus of \"[[cherry picking (fallacy)|cherry-picking]] statistics\" and \"massaging information\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/11/washington/11policy.html |work=The New York Times |title=Petraeus Warns Against Quick Pullback in Iraq |first1=David S. |last1=Cloud |first2=Thom |last2=Shanker |date=September 11, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Chairman of the [[House Foreign Affairs Committee]] [[Tom Lantos]] of [[California]] called the General and [[U.S. Ambassador to Iraq]] [[Ryan Crocker]] \"Two of our nation's most capable [[public servants]]\" and said Democrats feel \"esteem for their [[professionalism]]\". He also said that \"We can no longer take their assertions on Iraq at [[face value]]\"; concluding, \"We need to get out of Iraq, for that country's sake as well as our own.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/democratic-response-presidents-address/story.aspx?guid=%7BD8CCFF12-73A1-48D6-AEFB-860F4D3A2BBA%7D |title=Democratic response to president's address |publisher=MarketWatch |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[United States Republican Party|Republican]] [[United States Republican presidential candidates, 2008|Presidential candidate]] [[Duncan L. Hunter|Duncan Hunter]] called the report \"a candid, independent assessment given with integrity\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Cloud |first=David S. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/11/washington/11policy.html |title=Petraeus Warns Against Quick Pullback in Iraq |location=Iraq |work=The New York Times|date=September 11, 2007 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref> Republican Senator [[Jon Kyl]] of [[Arizona]] stated that \"I commend General Petraeus for his honest and forthright assessment of the situation in Iraq.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyl.senate.gov/record.cfm?id=282218 |title=Senator Jon Kyl Press Office |publisher=Kyl.senate.gov |date=September 10, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727170503/http://kyl.senate.gov/record.cfm?id=282218 |archivedate=July 27, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref> [[Opposition to the Iraq War#Opposition in the United States|Anti-war]] Republican Senator [[Chuck Hagel]] of [[Nebraska]] criticized the report while praising Petraeus, saying \"It's not your fault, general.... It's not [[Ambassador to Iraq|Ambassador]] [[Ryan Crocker|Crocker]]'s fault. It's this administration's fault.\"<ref>{{cite web|author1=Eric Weiner |author2=Scott Neuman |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14350283 |title=Political Junkie: The Impact of the Iraq Reports |publisher=NPR|accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> A ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Gallup poll]] taken after Petraeus's report to Congress showed virtually no change in public opinion toward the war.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2007-09-18-poll-iraq_N.htm |work=USA Today |title=Poll: Public not swayed by Petraeus |first=Susan |last=Page |date=September 19, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> A [[Pew Research Center]] survey found that most Americans who have heard about the report approve of Petraeus's recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people-press.org/reports/display.php3?ReportID=355 |title=Summary of Findings: Petraeus' Proposals Favored, But No Lift in War Support |publisher=People-press.org |date=September 18, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, the Senate passed an amendment by Republican [[John Cornyn III]] of [[Texas]] designed to \"strongly condemn personal attacks on the honor and integrity of General Petraeus\". Cornyn drafted the amendment in response to a [[MoveOn.org ad controversy|controversial full-page ad]] by the liberal group [[Moveon.org]] in the September 10, 2007, edition of ''[[The New York Times]]''. All forty-nine Republican Senators and twenty-two Democratic Senators voted in support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=110&session=1&vote=00344 |title=U.S. Senate: Legislation & Records Home \u2013 Votes \u2013 Roll Call Vote |publisher=U.S. Senate |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> The House passed a similar resolution by a 341\u201379 vote on September 26.\n\nIn December 2007, ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'s}} \"Fact Checker\" stated that \"While some of Petraeus's statistics are open to challenge, his claims about a general reduction in violence have been borne out over subsequent months. It now looks as if Petraeus was broadly right on this issue at least\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/fact-checker/2007/12/most_revealing_bloopers_hillar_1.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 1, 2010 |title=Most Revealing Fibs: Hillary Clinton |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523092212/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/fact-checker/2007/12/most_revealing_bloopers_hillar_1.html |archivedate=May 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBased on the conditions on the ground, in October 2007, Petraeus and [[U.S. Ambassador to Iraq]] [[Ryan Crocker]] revised their campaign plan for Iraq. In recognition of the progress made against Al Qaeda Iraq, one of the major points would be \"shifting the U.S. military effort to focus more on countering [[Private militias in Iraq|Shiite militias]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott |first=Ann |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/iraq/2003968504_iraqplan23.html |title=Finding a way forward in Iraq | work = The Seattle Times |date=October 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Multi-National Force&nbsp;\u2013 Iraq (spring 2008)====\nOn February 18, 2008, ''[[USA Today]]'' stated that \"the U.S. effort has shown more success\" and that, after the number of troops reached its peak in fall 2007, \"U.S. deaths were at their lowest levels since the 2003 invasion, civilian casualties were down, and street life was resuming in Baghdad.\"<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news|last=Dilanian |first=Ken |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2008-02-17-Iraqcongress_N.htm |title=Progress in Iraq reshapes debate over war |work=USA Today |date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> In light of the significant reduction in violence and as the surge brigades began to redeploy without replacement, Petraeus characterized the progress as tenuous, fragile, and reversible and repeatedly reminded all involved that much work remains to be done.<ref>Robinson, Linda. [https://www.usnews.com/articles/news/iraq/2008/01/17/a-generals-assessment.html \"Why David Petraeus Wants to Go Slowly on Troop Drawdowns\"], ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' January 17, 2008. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>Duffy, Michael. [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1708843,00.html \"The Surge At Year One\"] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' January 31, 2008. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> During an early February trip to Iraq, Defense Secretary [[Robert Gates]] endorsed the idea of a period of consolidation and evaluation upon completion of the withdrawal of surge brigades from Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/23105474 |title=Gates: US may slow Iraq drawdown |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus and Crocker continued these themes at their two full days of testimony before Congress on April 8 and 9. During his opening statement, Petraeus stated that \"there has been significant but uneven security progress in Iraq,\" while also noting that \"the situation in certain areas is still unsatisfactory and that innumerable challenges remain\" and that \"the progress made since last spring is fragile and reversible.\" He also recommended a continuation of the drawdown of surge forces as well as a 45-day period of consolidation and evaluation after the final surge brigade has redeployed in late July.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Analysts for ''[[USA Today]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that the hearings \"lacked the suspense of last September's debate\", but they did include sharp questioning as well as both skepticism and praise from various Congressional leaders.<ref>Myers, Stephen Lee and Thom Shanker. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/09/washington/09petraeus.html \"Petraeus Urges Halt in Weighing Troop New Cut in Force\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'' April 9, 2008. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>Michaels, Jim and David Jackson [https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2008-04-08-petraeus-iraq_N.htm \"Petraeus' Testimony Met with Praise, Skepticism\"] ''[[USA Today]]'' April 9, 2008. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn late May 2008, the [[Senate Armed Services Committee]] held nomination hearings for Petraeus and [[Raymond T. Odierno|Lieutenant General Ray Odierno]] to lead [[CENTCOM|United States Central Command]] and [[Multinational Force Iraq|Multi-National Force-Iraq]], respectively. During the hearings, Committee Chairman [[Carl Levin]] praised these two men, stating that \"we owe Gen. Petraeus and Gen. Odierno a debt of gratitude for the commitment, determination and strength that they brought to their areas of responsibility. And regardless of how long the administration may choose to remain engaged in the strife in that country, our troops are better off with the leadership these two distinguished soldiers provide.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown |first=Angela K. |url=http://www.salon.com/wires/ap/2008/05/22/D90QNMHO5_petraeus_confirmation/index.html |title=\"A Top Senate Democrat Signals Support for Petraeus\" Flaherty, Anne |work=Salon |date=May 22, 2008 |accessdate=May 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> During his opening statement, Petraeus discussed four principles that would guide his efforts if confirmed as [[CENTCOM]] Commander: seeking to strengthen international partnerships; taking a \"whole of government\" approach; pursuing comprehensive efforts and solutions; and, finally, both supporting efforts in Iraq and Afghanistan and ensuring readiness for possible contingency operations in the future. Petraeus also noted that during the week before his testimony, the number of security incidents in Iraq was the lowest in over four years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centcom.mil/en/posture-the-force/33.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414082251/http://www.centcom.mil/en/posture-the-force/33.html|url-status=dead|title=\"US Central Command Opening Statement\" May 22, 2008|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> After Petraeus's return to Baghdad, and despite the continued drawdown of surge forces as well as recent Iraqi-led operations in places like Basrah, Mosul, and Baghdad, the number of security incidents in Iraq remained at their lowest level in over four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=20093&Itemid=131 |title=Operational Update by MG Kevin Bergner, spokesman for Multi-National Force-Iraq, and MajGen Qassim Atta, spokesman for Operation Fardh Al Qanoon, Baghdad, Iraq, June 4, 2008 |publisher=Mnf-iraq.com |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214003137/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=20093&Itemid=131 |archivedate=February 14, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq (summer and fall 2008)====\n[[File:Barack Obama 2008 Iraq 2.jpg|thumb|Petraeus explains security improvements in [[Sadr City]] while giving an aerial tour of Baghdad to Senator [[Barack Obama]], July 2008]]\nIn September 2008, Petraeus gave an interview to [[BBC News]] stating that he did not think using the term \"victory\" in describing the Iraq war was appropriate, saying \"This is not the sort of struggle where you take a hill, plant the flag and go home to a victory parade... it's not war with a simple slogan.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7610405.stm |title=No victory in Iraq, says Petraeus |work=BBC News |date=September 11, 2008 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus had discussed the term 'victory' before in March 2008, saying to [[NPR News]] that \"an Iraq that is at peace with itself, at peace with its neighbors, that has a government that is representative of\u2014and responsive to\u2014its citizenry and is a contributing member of the global community\" could arguably be called 'victory'.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=88482985 Gen. Petraeus Defines Victory in Iraq]. NPR. Published March 18, 2008.</ref> On the eve of his change of command, in September 2008, Petraeus stated that \"I don't use terms like victory or defeat... I'm a realist, not an optimist or a pessimist. And the reality is that there has been significant progress but there are still serious challenges.\"<ref name=praise>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/16/world/middleeast/16gates.html | work=The New York Times | first1=Thom | last1=Shanker | first2=Stephen | last2=Farrell | title=Gates Praises Petraeus on Eve of Duty Transfer | date=September 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Change of command====\n[[File:DavidPetraeusAbdulQadir.jpg|left|thumb|Iraq Defense Minister [[Qadir Obeidi|Abdul Qadir]] presents a gift to Petraeus during a farewell ceremony in Baghdad on September 15, 2008.]]\n\nOn September 16, 2008, Petraeus formally gave over his command in Iraq to General [[Raymond T. Odierno]] in a government ceremony presided by Defense Secretary [[Robert Gates]].<ref name=praise/> During the ceremony, Gates stated that Petraeus \"played a historic role\" and created the \"translation of a great strategy into a great success in very difficult circumstances\". Gates also told Petraeus he believed \"history will regard you as one of our nation's greatest battle captains.\"<ref name=praise/> He presented Petraeus with the [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]].<ref name=praise/> At the event, Petraeus mentioned the difficulty in getting the [[Sons of Iraq]] absorbed in the central [[Government of Iraq]] and warned about future consequences if the effort stalls.<ref name=praise/> Indeed, when speaking of these and other challenges, Petraeus is the first to note that \"the gains [achieved in Iraq] are tenuous and unlikely to survive without an American effort that outlasts his tenure.\" Even so, as Petraeus departed Iraq, it was clear to all that he was leaving a much different Iraq than the one that existed when he took command in February 2007. As described by Dexter Filkins, \"violence has plummeted from its apocalyptic peaks, Iraqi leaders are asserting themselves, and streets that once seemed dead are flourishing with life.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Filkins |first=Dexter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/21/world/middleeast/21general.html |title=Exiting Iraq, Petraeus Says Gains Are Fragile |location=Iraq |work=The New York Times|date=August 20, 2008 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref> This is also illustrated by the Iraq Trends charts that the MNF-I produces weekly. The January 3, 2009, Iraq Trends chart clearly depicts over time, the increases in incidents followed by the sharp decline as described by Dexter Filkens and others.\n\nGeneral Petraeus's critical role in Iraq has been widely acknowledged by commands of the coalition forces. In her introduction of Petraeus at the Baccalaureate ceremony for the Class of 2009, [[Princeton University]] President Shirley Tilghman described his accomplishments. While acknowledging that much remains to be accomplished in Iraq, Tilghman paid tribute to Petraeus's \"leadership in rethinking American military strategy through his principles of counterinsurgency\", which are, she said, \"eliminating 'simplistic definitions of victory and defeat in favor of incremental and nuanced progress'\".<ref>MacPherson, K. (May 31, 2009). [https://www.princeton.edu/main/news/archive/S24/38/10A46/ Petraeus challenges seniors to pursue life of public service]. Princeton University: News at Princeton. Retrieved August 13, 2011.</ref>\n\n===U.S. Central Command (fall 2008 to summer 2010)===\n[[File:Petraeus at SAC.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Gen. David H. Petraeus speaking at the [[New Hampshire Institute of Politics]] at [[Saint Anselm College]]]]\nOn October 31, 2008, Petraeus assumed command of the [[United States Central Command]] (USCENTCOM) headquartered in Tampa, Florida. Petraeus was responsible for U.S. operations in 20 countries spreading from Egypt to Pakistan\u2014including Operations Iraqi Freedom and Enduring Freedom. During his time at CENTCOM, Petraeus advocated that countering the terrorist threats in the CENTCOM region requires more than just counter-terrorism forces, demanding instead whole-of-governments, comprehensive approaches akin to those of counterinsurgency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commander's speech: NCAFP George F. Kennan Award, Union League Club, NYC, May 28 |url=http://www.parade.com/news/2009/11/29-general-petraeus-gives-a-war-briefing.html |date=May 28, 2009 |first=Gen. David H. |last=Petraeus |publisher=U.S. Central Command |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> One of his closest colleagues said that Petraeus knew that defeating an insurgency required living among the people, convincing them that we were better than the insurgents.  \"[Y]ou can't kill 'em all ... . [Y]ou can't kill your way out of an insurgency. ... You have to find other kinds of ammunition, and it's not always a bullet.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Depaulo|first1=Lisa|title=Leader of the Year: Right Man, Right Time|url=https://www.gq.com/story/leader-of-the-year-general-david-petraeus-war|accessdate=February 19, 2017|magazine=GQ|date=October 31, 2008}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus reiterated this view in a 2009 interview published in ''Parade'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |title=General Petraeus Gives A War Briefing |url=http://www.parade.com/news/2009/11/29-general-petraeus-gives-a-war-briefing.html |date=November 29, 2009 |first=Col. Jack |last=Jacobs |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> In a recent interview for ''Newsweek'' magazine's \"Interview Issue: The View From People Who Make a Difference\", Petraeus expressed his support for President Obama's announced Afghanistan strategy and discussed his view that reconciliation efforts in Afghanistan should for the time being occur \"at the lower and midlevels\".<ref>{{Cite journal |title=The General |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/227759/page/1 |date=January 4, 2009 |first=Fareed |last=Zakaria |journal=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 18, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn mid-August 2009, Petraeus established the [[Afghanistan-Pakistan Center of Excellence]] within the USCENTCOM Directorate of [[Intelligence]] to provide leadership to coordinate, integrate and focus analysis efforts in support of operations in Afghanistan and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=4&section=0&article=125765&d=25&m=8&y=2009 |title=US CentCom establishes center for Afghanistan, Pakistan analysts |newspaper=Arab News |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=October 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213065600/http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=4&section=0&article=125765&d=25&m=8&y=2009 |archivedate=December 13, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2010, testimony to the [[Senate Armed Services Committee]], Petraeus described the continuing [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] as a challenge to U.S. interests in the region. According to the testimony, the conflict was \"fomenting anti-American sentiment\" due to \"a [[perception]] of U.S. favoritism for [[Israel]]\". This was widely commented on in the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.voanews.com/english/news/middle-east/US-General-Israeli-Palestinian-Conflict-Affects-US-Interests-87908632.html |title=US General: Israeli-Palestinian Conflict Affects US Interests |publisher=[[Voice of America News]] |date=March 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828192155/http://www.voanews.com/english/news/middle-east/US-General-Israeli-Palestinian-Conflict-Affects-US-Interests-87908632.html |archive-date=August 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://armed-services.senate.gov/statemnt/2010/03%20March/Petraeus%2003-16-10.pdf |title=Statement of General David H. Petraeus, U.S. Army Commander U.S. Central Command before the Senate Armed Services Committee on the Posture of U.S. Central Command Mar 16, 2010 |publisher=[[U.S. Senate]] |date=March 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331012029/http://armed-services.senate.gov/statemnt/2010/03%20March/Petraeus%2003-16-10.pdf |archivedate=March 31, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Ron |last=Kampeas|url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2010/03/18/1011222/adl-petraeus-testimony-counterproductive |title=ADL: Petraeus testimony 'counterproductive' |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |date=March 18, 2010 |accessdate=March 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/03/201031732237498901.html |title=US General: Perceived Israel bias 'hurts us' |work=[[Aljazeera]] |date=March 17, 2010 |accessdate=April 4, 2010}}</ref> When questioned by journalist Philip Klein, Petraeus said the original reporter \"picked apart\" and \"spun\" his speech. He believes there are many important factors standing in the way of peace, including \"a whole bunch of extremist organizations, some of which by the way deny Israel's right to exist. There's a country that has a nuclear program who denies that the [[Holocaust]] took place. So again we have all these factors in there. This [Israel] is just one.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Petraeus Sets the Record Straight on Israel |url=http://spectator.org/archives/2010/03/25/petraeus-sets-the-record-strai |date=March 25, 2010 |first=Philip |last=Klein |work=[[The American Spectator]] |accessdate=April 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330095535/http://spectator.org/archives/2010/03/25/petraeus-sets-the-record-strai/ |archivedate=March 30, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=From the Horse's Mouth: Petraeus on Israel |url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/boot/265971 |date=March 25, 2010 |first=Max |last=Boot |authorlink=Max Boot |journal=[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]] |accessdate=April 29, 2010 |publisher=[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Petraeus visited the [[New Hampshire Institute of Politics]] at [[Saint Anselm College]] to speak about Iraq and Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web |title=General David Petraeus speaks at St. Anselm College |url=http://www.necn.com/03/24/10/General-David-Petraeus-speaks-at-St-Anse/landing_nation.html?blockID=203840&feedID=4207 |date=March 24, 2010 |first=Lauren |last=Collins |work=[[New England Cable News]] |accessdate=April 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826154712/http://www.necn.com/03/24/10/General-David-Petraeus-speaks-at-St-Anse/landing_nation.html?blockID=203840&feedID=4207 |archivedate=August 26, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Petraeus spoke a few days after the seventh anniversary of the U.S. invasion of Iraq, noting the successful changes in Iraq since the U.S. [[troop surge]]. The visit to Saint Anselm created rumors that Petraeus was contemplating a run for the Presidency; however, he denied the speculation saying that he was not aware that the college has been the site of numerous presidential debates.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Petraeus Denies Presidential Primary Town Trip Is Linked to Politics |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/03/24/petraeus-denies-presidential-primary-town-trip-linked-politics/ |date=March 24, 2010 |publisher=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\nToward the close of his tenure as CENTCOM Commander, including in his interview published in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', Petraeus discussed the effort to determine and send to Afghanistan the right \"inputs\" for success there; these inputs include several structures and organizations that proved important in Iraq, including \"an engagement cell to support reconciliation ... a finance cell to go after financing of the enemy ... [a] really robust detainee-operations task force, a rule-of-law task force, an energy-fusion cell \u2013 all these other sort of nonstandard missions that are very important\".<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Professor of War |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2010/05/petraeus-201005/ |date=May 2010 |journal=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2010, ''The New York Times'' published an article that there was mounting evidence of a Taliban role in the Times Square bombing plot.<ref>{{cite news|title=Evidence Mounts for Taliban Role in Bomb Plot|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/06/nyregion/06bomb.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 5, 2010|first1=Mark|last1=Mazzetti|first2=Scott|last2=Shane}}</ref> On May 7, 2010, Petraeus announced that Times Square bombing suspect, [[Faisal Shahzad]], is a \"lone wolf\" terrorist who did not work with others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/05/07/national/main6468524.shtml |title=Gen. Petraeus: Shahzad Acted Alone |publisher=CBS News |date=May 7, 2010 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref> On May 10, 2010, Attorney General Eric Holder said that the evidence shows the Pakistani Taliban directed this plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/05/09/times.square.suspect/index.html |title=Holder: Pakistani Taliban helped direct Times Square plot |publisher=CNN |date=May 9, 2010 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Health====\nGeneral Petraeus was diagnosed with early-stage [[prostate cancer]] in February 2009 and underwent two months of successful [[radiation treatment]] at [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicallyillustrated.com/index.php?/page/usa/1452/|title=David Petraeus Collapses During Senate Hearing|work=Politically Illustrated|date=June 15, 2010|accessdate=July 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715102224/http://politicallyillustrated.com/index.php?%2Fpage%2Fusa%2F1452%2F|archivedate=July 15, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The diagnosis and treatment was not publicly disclosed until October 2009 because Petraeus and his family regarded his illness as a personal matter that did not interfere with the performance of his duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/06/world/middleeast/06petraeus.html|work=The New York Times |title=General Petraeus Has Prostate Cancer|first=Eric|last=Schmitt|date=October 6, 2009|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2010, Petraeus momentarily fainted while being questioned by the Senate Armed Services Committee. He quickly recovered and was able to walk and exit the room without assistance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/onpolitics/post/2010/06/gen-david-petraeus-passes-out-on-capitol-hill/1|title=Gen. David Petraeus passes out on Capitol Hill \u2013 On Politics: Covering the US Congress, Governors, and the 2010 Election |work=USA Today|date=June 15, 2010 |accessdate=July 4, 2010|first=John|last=Fritze}}</ref> He attributed the episode to possible [[dehydration]].\n\n===Commander of U.S. and ISAF forces in Afghanistan===\n[[File:Officials meet near the 'friendship brdige' border crossing between Mangusar, Uzbekistan and Hairatan, Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|right|Petraeus having tea with the [[Afghan Border Police]] Commander at the border with Uzbekistan]]\nOn June 23, 2010, President Obama announced that he would nominate Petraeus to succeed General [[Stanley A. McChrystal]] as the commander of U.S. Forces in Afghanistan. The change of command was prompted by McChrystal's comments about the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] and its policies in Afghanistan during an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/> The nomination was technically a positional step down from his position as commander of Central Command, however the President said that he believed that he was the best man for the job. After being confirmed by the Senate on June 30,<ref name=\"petraeus confirmed IT\" /> Petraeus formally assumed command on July 4.<ref name=\"CBC-2010/07/03/petraeus-afghanistan\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/petraeus-takes-command-in-afghanistan-1.887818 |title=Petraeus takes command in Afghanistan |date=July 4, 2010 |publisher=CBC News |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> During the assumption of command remarks,<ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by Gen. David H. Petraeus upon Assumption of Command |date=July 4, 2010 |publisher=International Security Assistance Force, Afghanistan |url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/transcripts/isaf-commanders-remarks-upon-assumption-of-command.html |accessdate=July 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715104920/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/transcripts/isaf-commanders-remarks-upon-assumption-of-command.html |archivedate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> Petraeus provided his vision and goals to NATO, the members of his command, and his Afghan partners. As he was known to do while the Commander in Iraq, Petraeus delivered his first Letter to the Troops<ref>{{cite web |title=Letter to the Troops from Gen. David H. Petraeus |date=July 4, 2010 |publisher=International Security Assistance Force, Afghanistan |url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/news/a-word-from-the-commander.html |accessdate=July 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100708163053/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/news/a-word-from-the-commander.html |archivedate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> on the same day he assumed command.<ref>{{cite web |author=Al Pessin |url=http://www1.voanews.com/english/news/Petraeus-Issues-First-Guidance-to-Allied-Troops-in-Afghanistan-99785884.html |title=Petraeus Issues First Guidance to Allied Troops in Afghanistan |publisher=VOA News |date=August 2, 2010 |accessdate=October 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926191555/http://www.voanews.com/english/news/Petraeus-Issues-First-Guidance-to-Allied-Troops-in-Afghanistan-99785884.html |archive-date=September 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2010, shortly after the disclosure of the [[Afghan War Diary|Afghan war logs]] on [[WikiLeaks]], Petraeus issued his updated Tactical Directive for the prevention of civilian casualties, providing guidance and intent for the use of force by the U.S. military units operating in Afghanistan (replacing the July 1, 2009, version). This directive reinforced the concept of \"disciplined use of force in partnership with Afghan Security Forces\" in the fight against insurgent forces.\n\n{{quote|We must never forget that the center of gravity in this struggle is the Afghan people; it is they who will ultimately determine the future of Afghanistan ... Prior to the use of fires, the commander approving the strike must determine that no civilians are present. If unable to assess the risk of civilian presence, fires are prohibited, except under of the following two conditions (specific conditions deleted due to operational security; however, they have to do with the risk to ISAF and Afghan forces).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centcom.mil/news/gen-petraeus-updates-guidance-on-use-of-force |title=Gen. Petraeus updates guidance on use of force |publisher=Centcom.mil |accessdate=May 21, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the October 2010 issue of ''Army Magazine'', Petraeus discussed changes that had taken place over the previous 18 months, including sections discussing \"setting the conditions for progress\", \"capitalizing on the conditions for progress\", \"improving security\", \"supporting governance expansion\", \"promoting economic development\", \"reducing corruption\", and \"our troopers: carrying out a difficult mission\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ausa.org/publications/armymagazine/archive/2010/10/Documents/Petraeus_1010.pdf |title=Setting\u2014and Capitalizing on\u2014 Conditions for Progress in Afghanistan |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Defense.gov News Photo 100805-F-7552L-211 - Commander of the International Security Assistance Force Gen. David H. Petraeus center U.S. Army talks with U.S. soldiers of the 2nd Battalion.jpg|thumb|Petraeus talks with U.S. soldiers at Combat Outpost Monti in eastern Afghanistan on August 5, 2010.]]\n[[File:Flickr - The U.S. Army - Gen. Petraeus visit.jpg|thumb|Petraeus visits Regional Command West in Afghanistan, May 16, 2011.]]\n\nAs commander in Afghanistan, Petraeus joined President Obama as a primary target for Osama bin Laden. Documents recovered from bin Laden\u2019s compound after his death unveiled a plot to assassinate the two men together as they traveled by plane. Bin Laden\u2019s communications with a top deputy stated, \"The reason for concentrating on them is that Obama is the head of infidelity and killing him automatically will make [Vice President] Biden take over the presidency. Biden is totally unprepared for that post, which will lead the U.S. into a crisis. As for Petraeus, he is the man of the hour... and killing him would alter the war's path\" in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-bin-laden-plot-to-kill-president-obama/2012/03/16/gIQAwN5RGS_story.html |publisher=The Washington Post |title=The bin Laden plot to kill President Obama |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/osama-bin-laden-wanted-to-kill-obama-so-biden-would-be-president-declassified-docs-show |publisher=FOX News |title=Usama bin Laden wanted to kill Obama so 'totally unprepared' Biden would be president, declassified docs show |date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2011, Petraeus made a \"rare apology\" following a NATO helicopter airstrike under his command that resulted in the deaths of nine Afghan boys and the wounding of a 10th, as they gathered firewood in Eastern Afghanistan. In a statement, Petraeus apologized to the members of the Afghan government, the people of Afghanistan and the surviving family members, and said: \"These deaths should have never happened.\" Several journalists and observers noted the humanitarian candor in Petraeus's open regrets.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/03/world/asia/03afghan.html \"Nine Afghan Boys Collecting Firewood Killed by NATO Helicopters\"], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Nissenbaum |first=Dion |author2=Habib Khan Totakhil |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704728004576176644160681276 |title=Coalition Apologizes for Deaths of Afghan Children |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 3, 2011 |accessdate=October 1, 2011}}</ref> Petraeus relinquished command of U.S. and NATO forces in Afghanistan on July 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/07/18/afghanistan.petraeus.handover/index.html |publisher=CNN |title=Petraeus hands over command in Afghanistan |date=July 18, 2011}}</ref> He received the Defense Distinguished Service Medal and the NATO Meritorious Service Medal for his service.\n\n==Retirement from the U.S. Army==\nPetraeus retired from the U.S. Army on August 31, 2011. His retirement ceremony was held at [[Joint Base Myer\u2013Henderson Hall]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defense.gov//News/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=65213 |title=Petraeus Garners Praise at Retirement Ceremony |date=August 31, 2011 |author=Jim Garamone |publisher=American Forces Press Service |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714204202/http://www.defense.gov//News/NewsArticle.aspx?ID=45180 |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> During this ceremony, he was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] by [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]] [[William J. Lynn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/08/ap-petraeus-troop-support-must-be-top-priority-083111/|title=Petraeus: Budget cuts must not impair military|date=August 31, 2011|author1=Kimberly Dozier |author2=Robert Burns |agency=Associated Press |work=Army Times |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref> During the ceremony, Lynn noted that Petraeus had played an important role as both a combat leader and strategist in the post-9/11 world. Lynn also cited General Petraeus's efforts in current counter insurgency strategy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1602 |title=Remarks at the Retirement Ceremony for General David H. Petraeus|date=August 31, 2011|publisher=U.S. Department of Defense|accessdate=September 1, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018045113/http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1602|archivedate=October 18, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Admiral [[Michael Mullen]], [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] in his remarks compared General Petraeus to [[Ulysses S. Grant]], [[John J. Pershing]], [[George Marshall]] and [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] as one of the great battle captains of American history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jcs.mil/speech.aspx?ID=1642|title=Armed forces farewell tribute and retirement ceremony in honor of Gen. David H. Petraeus|date=August 31, 2011|publisher=Joint Chiefs of Staff|accessdate=September 1, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103152742/http://www.jcs.mil/speech.aspx?ID=1642|archivedate=November 3, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> With his four-star rank, Petraeus receives an annual pension of about $220,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2016/01/30/pentagon-not-dock-petraeus-star/79564214/ |title=Pentagon won't demote Petraeus for sharing classified information |author=Tom Vanden Brook |date=January 30, 2016 |work=USA Today |accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Dates of rank===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Promotions\n! Rank !! Date\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O1 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Second lieutenant]]||1974<ref name=110thCongress>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/110/chrg/shrg46092/CHRG-110shrg46092.pdf|title=Nominations Before the Senate Armed Services Committee, Second Session, 110th Congress}}</ref>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O2 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[First lieutenant (United States)|First lieutenant]]||1976<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O3 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]||1978<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O4 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Major (United States)|Major]]||1985<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O5 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]]||1991<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O6 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]||1995<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O7 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier general]]||2000<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O8 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major general]]||2003<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O9 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant general]]||2004<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|-\n||[[File:US Army O10 shoulderboard rotated.svg|120px]] [[General (United States)|General]]||2007<ref name=110thCongress/>\n|}\n\n==CIA Director==\n[[File:Petraeus ceremonially sworn in as CIA Director.jpg|thumb|left|Petraeus ceremonially sworn in at CIA Headquarters as his wife, [[Holly Petraeus|Holly]], looks on]]\nOn April 28, 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] announced that he had nominated Petraeus to become the new [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/28/obama-announces-changes-to-national-security-team/?ref=politics|work=The New York Times|first=Michael D.|last=Shear|title=Obama Announces Changes to National Security Team|date=April 28, 2011}}</ref> The nomination was confirmed by the United States Senate 94\u20130 on June 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-petraeus-confirmed-20110630,0,6226030.story|title= Senate confirms David Petraeus as CIA director|date=June 30, 2011|author=Kathleen Hennessey|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate= June 30, 2011}} For the three Democrats and three Republicans who did not cast a vote on this confirmation, see [[Confirmations of Barack Obama's Cabinet#Confirmation roll call votes|Obama confirmations, 2010]].</ref> Petraeus was sworn in at the White House on September 6<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/news-information/press-releases-statements/press-release-2011/david-h.-petraeus-takes-helm-as-director-of-the-central-intelligence-agency.html David H. Petraeus Takes Helm as Director of the Central Intelligence Agency] ''cia.gov'' September 6, 2011</ref> and then ceremonially sworn in by Vice President [[Joe Biden]] at CIA Headquarters in Langley, Virginia on October 11, 2011.<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/news-information/press-releases-statements/press-release-2011/vice-president-biden-visits-cia-headquarters-for-ceremony-with-director-petraeus.html Vice President Biden Visits CIA Headquarters for Ceremony with Director Petraeus] ''cia.gov'' October 12, 2011</ref>\n\nPetraeus's tenure at the CIA was more low profile than that of his predecessor, [[Leon Panetta]], declining to give media interviews while Director and speaking to Congress in [[Closed session of the United States Congress|closed sessions]]. He also differed from Panetta in management style, as an article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' published just days before his resignation said Panetta \"wooed the work force and often did not question operational details, [while] Petraeus is a demanding boss who does not hesitate to order substandard work redone or details of plans adjusted\".<ref name=\"NYTnov2\">Scott Shane, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/03/world/africa/petraeuss-lower-profile-at-cia-leaves-void-in-benghazi-furor.html Petraeus's Quieter Style at C.I.A. Leaves Void on Libya Furor] ''[[The New York Times]]'' November 2, 2012</ref>\n\nAlthough Petraeus was given good marks by most observers for his work heading the CIA,<ref name=\"NYTnov2\"/> during October 2012 some critics took issue with the availability of accurate information from the CIA concerning a [[Attack on the U.S. diplomatic mission in Benghazi|terrorist attack in Benghazi, Libya]], the month prior. On September 11 four Americans had been killed, including the Ambassador, and more than thirty evacuated. Only seven of those evacuated did not work for the CIA. According to a ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' story, other government agencies complained about being left \"largely in the dark about the CIA's role\", with Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] telephoning Petraeus directly the night of the attacks seeking assistance. Although the \"State Department believed it had a formal agreement with the CIA to provide backup security\", \"the CIA didn't have the same understanding about its security responsibilities,\" said ''The Wall Street Journal''.<ref>Adam Entous, Siobhan Gorman, and Margaret Coker [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204712904578092853621061838 CIA Takes Heat for Role in Libya] ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' November 1, 2012</ref>\n\n==Extramarital affair, resignation and criticism==\n{{Main|Petraeus scandal}}\n[[File:David Petraeus and Paula Broadwell.jpg|thumb|Petraeus with [[Paula Broadwell]] in July 2011]]\n\nPetraeus reportedly began an affair with [[Paula Broadwell]], principal author of his biography, ''[[All In: The Education of General David Petraeus]]'', after Petraeus left his ISAF command on July 18, 2011, to become CIA director. Petraeus reportedly ended the affair in the summer of 2012, around the time that he learned that Broadwell had been sending harassing emails to a longstanding family friend of the Petraeuses, [[Jill Kelley]].<ref name=\"WaPoNov12\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/petraeus-told-biographer-to-stop-harassing-family-friend-officials-say/2012/11/12/6ccb325c-2d00-11e2-a99d-5c4203af7b7a_story.html Petraeus told biographer to stop harassing family friend, officials say] ''[[The Washington Post]]'' November 12, 2012</ref>\n\nKelley, a Florida socialite who frequently entertained senior military personnel at her and her husband's [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] mansion,<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/11/13/florida-housewife-in-petraeus-scandal-reportedly-never-spared-anything-for/ \"The other ... other woman: Florida housewife emerges at center of Petraeus scandal\"] ''[[FOX News]]'' November 13, 2012</ref> had approached an acquaintance who worked for the [[FBI Tampa Field Office]] in the late spring with regard to anonymous emails she considered threatening.<ref name=\"WaPoNov12\"/> The Bureau traced the emails to Broadwell, and noted that Broadwell appeared to be exchanging intimate messages with an email account belonging to Petraeus, which instigated an investigation into whether that account had been hacked into or was someone posing as Petraeus.<ref>Scott Shane and Charlie Savage, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/12/us/us-officials-say-petraeuss-affair-known-in-summer.html Officials Say F.B.I. Knew of Petraeus Affair in the Summer] ''[[The New York Times]]'' November 11, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/11/09/petraeus-resigns-as-cia-director/ Petraeus resigns after affair with biographer turned up in FBI probe, Fox News confirms] FOX News, November 9, 2012</ref><ref>[http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/09/15056607-petraeus-biographer-paula-broadwell-under-fbi-investigation-over-access-to-his-email-law-enforcement-officials-say?lite Petraeus' biographer Paula Broadwell under FBI investigation over access to his email, law enforcement officials say] NBC News, November 9, 2012</ref> According to an [[Associated Press]] report, rather than transmit emails to each other's inbox, which would have left a more obvious email trail, Petraeus and Broadwell left messages in a draft folder and the draft messages were then [[Foldering|read by the other person]] when they logged into the same account.<ref>Kimberly Dozier and Pete Yost, [http://m.apnews.com/ap/db_289563/contentdetail.htm?contentguid=VOlvNjF4 Petraeus shocked to hear of emails, associates say] ''[[Associated Press]]'' November 12, 2012</ref>\n\nAlthough [[US Attorney General]] [[Eric Holder]] was aware that the FBI had discovered the affair,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/11/12/holder-notified-petraeus-probe-in-late-summer/ | work=Fox News | title=Holder notified of Petraeus probe in late summer -- did he tell anyone? | date=November 12, 2012}}</ref> it was not until November 6, 2012, that Petraeus's nominal superior, Director of National Intelligence [[James R. Clapper]], was advised. That same evening Clapper called Petraeus and urged him to resign. Clapper notified the [[White House]] the next day, November 7. After being briefed on November 8, President Obama summoned Petraeus to the White House where Petraeus offered his resignation.<ref>Sari Horwitz and Greg Miller, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-probe-of-petraeus-triggered-by-e-mail-threats-from-biographer-officials-say/2012/11/10/d2fc52de-2b68-11e2-bab2-eda299503684_story_2.html FBI probe of Petraeus triggered by e-mail threats from biographer, officials say] ''The Washington Post'' November 11, 2012</ref> Obama accepted his resignation on November 9,<ref>[http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2012/11/09/source-cia-director-david-petraeus-submits-resignation-over-extra-marital-affair/?hpt=hp_t1 CIA director David Petraeus resigns over extramarital affair] CNN, November 9, 2012</ref> and Petraeus cited his affair when announcing that same day that he would resign as CIA Director.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/CIA-chief-David-Petraeus-resignation-over-extramarital-affair-shocks-Washington/articleshow/17171843.cms |title=CIA chief David Petraeus' resignation over extramarital affair shocks Washington |accessdate=November 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |work=The Times Of India |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110142310/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/CIA-chief-David-Petraeus-resignation-over-extramarital-affair-shocks-Washington/articleshow/17171843.cms |archivedate=November 10, 2012 }}</ref> Eventually, Petraeus pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of mishandling the classified information that he provided to his mistress and biographer.<ref name=\"Mar 3 2015\"/>\n\n===Criticism after 2012 scandal===\nPetraeus had a strategy to influence military conditions by using press relations, both in [[Theater (warfare)|theater]] and in Washington, according to critics of his military career. On November 13, 2012, Reagan administration Assistant Secretary of Defense [[Lawrence Korb]], C.I.A. analyst and [[Veteran Intelligence Professionals for Sanity]] co-founder [[Ray McGovern]], and [[investigative journalist]] [[Gareth Porter]] appeared on [[Al Jazeera English]]. Together they assessed the general's extensive military-media strategy linking his writings on counterguerrilla operations and subsequent military media efforts, to his downfall with his female biographer. Critics said that the Petraeus media strategy would prove damaging for American policy in the future because of omissions and distorted interpretations that Washington policymakers, other experts, and the American public accepted from Petraeus's media contacts.<ref>{{Citation | contribution = David Petraeus: A US war hero? | first = Kimberly | last = Halkett | title = Inside Story Americas | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = November 13, 2012 | accessdate = November 16, 2012 | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/insidestoryamericas/2012/11/2012111393726260587.html}}.</ref>\n\nMilitary historians have noted the absence of field records for the Iraq and Afghanistan military campaigns, but have not personally been critical of the commanders in theater.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Sleeth | first1 = Peter | last2 = Bernton | first2 = Hal | date = November 9, 2012 | title = Lost to History: Missing War Records Complicate Benefit Claims by Iraq, Afghanistan Veterans | publisher = ProPublica | accessdate = November 12, 2012 | url = https://www.propublica.org/article/lost-to-history-missing-war-records-complicate-benefit-claims-by-veterans}}.</ref> One additional aspect of Petraeus's career that has come under increased scrutiny since his affair came to light has been his lack of a direct combat record in relation to the many awards he received. In particular, his Bronze Star Medal with Valor device has been mentioned in several media reports and questioned by several former Army officers.<ref>{{Citation | contribution = Petraeus Allegedly Earned A Bronze Star For Combat Valor 'Without Firing his Rifle' | first = Geoffrey | last = Ingersoll | title = Business Insider | publisher = Business Insider | date = November 16, 2012 | accessdate = December 18, 2012 | url = http://www.businessinsider.com/patraeus-allegedly-earned-a-bronze-star-for-combat-valor-without-firing-his-rifle-2012-11}}.</ref> The citation for Petraeus's Bronze Star with \"V\" device also notes his \"leadership under fire\", as does award of the Combat Action Badge, but neither provides a detailed account of his actions.\n\n===Criminal charges and probation===\nIn January 2015, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] and the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] had recommended bringing felony charges against Petraeus for providing classified information to [[Paula Broadwell|Broadwell]]. Petraeus denied the allegations and was reported to have had no interest in a plea deal.<ref name=\"https\"/> However, on Tuesday, March 3, 2015, the U.S. Justice Department announced that Petraeus agreed to plead guilty in federal court in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] to a charge of unauthorized removal and retention of classified information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/former-cia-director-petraeus-pleads-guilty-to-federal-charge-doj/ar-BBibqYX|title=Ex-CIA chief Petraeus to plead guilty, admits giving mistress secrets|publisher=MSN.com|access-date=March 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150305163640/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/crime/former-cia-director-petraeus-pleads-guilty-to-federal-charge-doj/ar-BBibqYX|archive-date=March 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the 15 page statement of facts filed by the government along with the plea agreement, the government stated that Petraeus had provided Broadwell access to documents containing Top Secret [[Sensitive Compartmented Information]], had later moved those documents to his personal residence and stored them in an unsecured drawer, and had deliberately and intentionally lied to Federal investigators about both providing Broadwell access to the documents and their improper storage. These facts were acknowledged to be true by Petraeus as part of his plea agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2015/03/03/theres-code-word-stuff-in-there-case-against-david-petraeus-laid-out-in-court-documents|title='There's code word stuff in there': Case against David Petraeus laid out in court documents|last=Lamothe|first=Dan|work=The Washington Post|date=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2015, a federal judge sentenced Petraeus to two years probation plus a fine of $100,000. The fine was more than double the amount the Justice Department had requested.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/24/us/david-petraeus-to-be-sentenced-in-leak-investigation.html |title=David Petraeus Is Sentenced to Probation in Leak Investigation |date=April 23, 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPress accounts in January 2016 indicated that Department of Defense staff were reviewing Department of Justice documents from the Petraeus prosecution and considering whether to recommend to the Secretary of Defense that Petraeus be demoted on the Army's retired list. Laws and regulations indicate that members of the military are retired at the last rank in which they are deemed to have served successfully; Petraeus's admission of an extramarital affair and guilty plea with regard to removing and retaining classified information while serving in the grade of general could be grounds for reduction in rank to lieutenant general. The matter was reviewed by then-Secretary of the Army [[John M. McHugh]] before he left office in October 2015; he recommended no further action.<ref>{{cite news |last=Starr |first=Barbara |date=January 19, 2016 |title=Demotion for Petraeus an option as Pentagon reviews case |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/19/politics/david-petraeus-defense-department/ |publisher=CNN |location=Atlanta}}</ref> On January 29, press accounts indicated that Stephen C. Hedger, Assistant Secretary of Defense for Legislative Affairs, had written to the U.S. Senate [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services Committee]]. In his letter, Hedger informed the committee that Secretary of Defense [[Ashton Carter]] had concurred with the Army's recommendation, and would not impose any further punishment on Petraeus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-decides-no-further-punishment-warranted-for-petraeus/2016/01/30/b503348e-c767-11e5-8965-0607e0e265ce_story.html |title=Pentagon won\u2019t punish David Petraeus any further in sex-and-secrets scandal|last1=Whitlock|first1=Craig|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|work=The Washington Post|date=January 30, 2016|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Activities in retirement==\nOn March 28, 2013, Petraeus joined [[American Corporate Partners]], a national [[nonprofit organization]] that connects post-[[September 11 attacks|9/11]] veterans to business professionals for career guidance. In March 2013, Petraeus accepted the role of Honorary Chairman of the [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] Society.<ref>{{cite web|title=William J. Donovan Award Dinner|publisher=The OSS Society|date=October 26, 2013|url=http://www.osssociety.org/pdfs/Invite_PDF_Response.pdf|accessdate=February 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus was named a [[visiting professor]] at [[Macaulay Honors College]] at the [[City University of New York]] in July 2013. According to a statement from Petraeus, \"I look forward to leading a seminar at Macaulay that examines the developments that could position the United States\u2014and our North American partners\u2014to lead the world out of the current global economic slowdown.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://security.blogs.cnn.com/2013/04/23/new-role-for-david-petraeus-professor/|title=New Role for David Petraeus: Professor |date=April 23, 2013 |publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref> After his anticipated $200,000 salary for the academic year drew fire from critics, Petraeus agreed to take on the teaching position [[One-dollar salary|for just $1]] in order to keep the focus on the students and away from any monetary controversy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/15/petraeus-cia-salary-cuny/2519705/ |title=Ex-CIA director Petraeus accepts $1-a-year job |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> In September 2013 Petraeus was harassed by students at CUNY while walking on campus.<ref>[http://blogs.militarytimes.com/flightlines/2013/09/11/college-students-harass-retired-gen-david-petraeus/ UPDATE: College students harass retired Gen. David Petraeus] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914205647/http://blogs.militarytimes.com/flightlines/2013/09/11/college-students-harass-retired-gen-david-petraeus/ |date=September 14, 2013 }} ''Military Times'' September 9, 2013</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2013, the [[University of Southern California]] named David Petraeus as a Judge Widney Professor, \"a title reserved for eminent individuals from the arts, sciences, professions, business and community and national leadership\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2013/05/gen_david_petraeus_joins.php |title=Gen. David Petraeus joins faculty at USC |date=May 2, 2013 |publisher=LA Observed |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> The president of the Currahee Board of Trustees announced May 6, 2013, that Petraeus agreed to serve on the board of trustees that preserves [[Camp Toccoa]]. During WWII, four of the main parachute infantry regiments of the Army trained at Camp Toccoa prior to their deployment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/section/6/article/83420/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130629080245/http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/section/6/article/83420/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 29, 2013 |title=Former Gen. Petraeus to serve on Camp Toccoa board |date=May 7, 2013 |newspaper=Gainesville Times |accessdate=May 7, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts|Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. L.P.]], a New York [[investment firm]], hired Petraeus as chairman of the firm's newly created KKR Global Institute in May 2013. Petraeus will support its investment teams and portfolio companies when studying new investments, especially in new locations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/05/david-petraeus-kkr-global-institute-92024.html/ |title=David Petraeus joins private-equity firm KKR |date=May 30, 2013 |newspaper=Politico |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> In December 2014, Petraeus was named a partner at KKR and remains Chairman of the KKR Global Institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kkr.com/our-firm/leadership/david-h-petraeus |title=David H. Petraeus Member, Chairman of the KKR Global Institute |accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus joined the board of advisers of [[Team Rubicon]] on June 18, 2013.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://teamrubiconusa.org/press-release-gen-david-petraeus-joins-team-rubicons-board-of-advisors/ |title=Gen. David Petraeus Joins Team Rubicon's Board of Advisors |date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707034649/http://teamrubiconusa.org/press-release-gen-david-petraeus-joins-team-rubicons-board-of-advisors/ |archivedate=July 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Royal United Services Institute]] (RUSI) named Petraeus as a Senior Vice President of the organization in August 2013. According to RUSI, \"The honorary role was created by RUSI's trustees and advisory council in recognition of General Petraeus's long association with the Institute and his distinguished contribution to the study and development of defence and international security concepts, as well as his implementation of those concepts in operations in the Balkans, Iraq, and Afghanistan.\"<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://my.rusi.org/newsletter/focus-august-2013?erid=1993818&trid=07441806-7cb5-48ae-a21a-6ecf69f63359 |title=General (Retd) David H Petraeus named RUSI Senior Vice President |date=August 20, 2013 |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Petraeus joined the Harvard's [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] as a non-resident senior fellow at the [[Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs]]. According to the school, Petraeus will jointly lead a new project focusing on the technological, scientific and economic dynamics that are spurring renewed North American competitiveness. \"The Coming North America Decades\" project will analyze how potential policy choices could effect this ongoing transformation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Petraeus joins Harvard's Kennedy School|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2013/oct/20/us-petraeus-harvard|newspaper=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=October 21, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021211951/http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2013/oct/20/us-petraeus-harvard/|archivedate=October 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  In 2016, the Center announced a new project involving Petraeus and focusing on strategic leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=David Petraeus on Strategic Leadership |url=http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/PetraeusStrategicLeadership/ |publisher=[[Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs]], [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], [[Harvard University]] |accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2014, the [[University of Exeter]] in England named Petraeus as an Honorary Visiting Professor of the Strategy and Security Institute. Alongside the other honorary faculty, the appointment will help inform the Institute's key objectives of exploring policymaking, strategy, and security.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our network |url=https://www.exeter.ac.uk/strategy/people/honoraryappointments/ |publisher=[[University of Exeter]] Strategy and Security Institute |accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJune 10, 2016, Petraeus and [[Mark Kelly]], a retired NASA astronaut, announced the creation of the gun control group Veterans Coalition for Common Sense.<ref>{{cite news|title=David Petraeus, Mark Kelly launch gun control group|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/10/politics/david-petraeus-mark-kelly-gun-control/|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus delivered the inaugural lecture in a series dedicated to his mentor and the former Dean of [[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy|The Fletcher School]] at [[Tufts University]], [[John Galvin (general)|General Jack Galvin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=David Petreaus Visits Campus, Discusses Time as Commander of U.S., Allied Forces in Iraq and Afghanistan |url=http://fletcher.tufts.edu/News-and-Media/2016/03/10/David-Petreaus-Inaugurates-John-R-Galvin-Lecture-Series |website=Tufts Fletcher School |date=March 10, 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He also delivered the inaugural lecture in a series dedicated to Admiral [[Stansfield Turner]] at the U.S. [[Naval War College]] on August 7, 2018. The lecture series honors the achievements of Turner, who served as the College's president from 1972-1974.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ullman |first1=Harlan |title=Stansfield Turner, David Petraeus true soldiers, scholars, statesmen |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/Voices/2018/08/06/Stansfield-Turner-David-Petraeus-true-soldiers-scholars-statesmen/1151533556982/ |work=United Press International |date=August 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a member of [[panel discussion]] in October 2018 concerning a film documenting the ''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'' newspaper, Petraeus shared his personal experiences with the newspaper with the audience.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sturgeon |first1=Kenna|title=Film celebrating Stars and Stripes military newspaper premieres in DC |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/in-the-know/in-the-know/409439-film-celebrating-stars-and-stripes-military-newspaper-premieres |work=The Hill|date=Oct 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, 2019, Petraeus accepted the invitation of a three-year Honorary Professorship in the Institute of Conflict, Cooperation and Security (ICSS) at the [[University of Birmingham]] in England. The university's announcement of the appointment stated that Petraeus \"will share insights from his career with students and researchers through a variety of interactions in Birmingham and virtually.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/news/latest/2019/06/general-david-petraeus-joins-institute-for-conflict-cooperation-and-security.aspx |title=General David Petraeus joins Institute for Conflict, Cooperation and Security |date=June 12, 2019 |publisher=University of Birmingham |accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Secretary of State consideration==\nOn November 18, 2016, an article by ''The Guardian'' cited \"diplomatic sources\" as having said that Petraeus had entered the race for Secretary of State in [[Donald Trump]]'s administration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Borger|first1=Julian|last2=Smith|first2=David|title=Michael Flynn said to be offered job of Trump national security adviser |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/nov/17/david-petraeus-secretary-of-state-donald-trump|work=The Guardian|date=November 18, 2016}}</ref> Petraeus confirmed his interest in the position during a BBC Radio 4 interview, stating that he would serve if asked.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clarke|first1=Hilary|title=Petraeus says he is willing to serve in Trump administration |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/23/politics/petraeus-interview-trump-administration/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=November 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus met with then President-elect Donald Trump at [[Trump Tower]] on November 28 to discuss the position and world affairs. Both Petraeus and Trump expressed favorable views of the meeting, with Trump taking to Twitter to announce, \"Just met with General Petraeus\u2014was very impressed!\" Petraeus joined a short list of potential candidates for the position, including [[Mitt Romney]] and [[Rudolph Giuliani|Rudy Giuliani]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landler|first1=Mark|title=David Petraeus, Secretary of State Candidate, Meets With Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/28/us/politics/donald-trump-transition-david-petraeus.html|work=The New York Times|date=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere was public speculation that his nomination could hurt Trump's administration, but Republican Senators [[John McCain]] and [[Lindsey Graham]] advocated for Petraeus, calling him \"an extraordinary pick.\" Petraeus also received support from Democratic Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]], suggesting that Democrats would keep an open mind concerning his confirmation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landler|first1=Mark|last2=Steinhauer|first2=Jennifer|title=Secretary of State David Petraeus? Supporters Make Their Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/us/politics/david-petraeus-trump-state-department.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2016, Trump officially selected [[Rex Tillerson]] for the role of Secretary of State. Petraeus expressed his gratitude for Trump's consideration and deferred to former Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]]' endorsement when asked his opinion of Tillerson.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lippman|first1=Daniel|title=Petraeus: I\u2019m \u2018grateful\u2019 Trump considered me for secretary of state|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/donald-trump-administration/2016/12/petraeus-im-grateful-trump-considered-me-for-secretary-of-state-232576|work=Politico|date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAccording to Petraeus, he does not vote in elections, having stopped following his promotion to [[major general]] in 2002 as part of a desire to be seen as apolitical. He has confirmed that he did not vote in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Coll|first1=Steve|title=THE GENERAL\u2019S DILEMMA|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/09/08/the-generals-dilemma|accessdate=December 4, 2016|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=September 8, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shelbourne|first1=Mallory|title='Apolitical' Petraeus says he did not vote in election|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/308673-petraeus-says-he-did-not-cast-a-ballot-in-election|accessdate=December 4, 2016|work=The Hill|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Organizational memberships==\n*Co-Chairman, Task Force on North America, Council on Foreign Relations (June 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/world/new-york-launch-cfr-sponsored-independent-task-force-report-north-america-time-new-focus/p35731|title=New York Launch of the CFR-Sponsored Independent Task Force Report \"North America: Time for a New Focus\"|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Directors, Atlantic Council (April 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/about/board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*Washington Speakers Bureau (June 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonspeakers.com/speakers/speaker.cfm?SpeakerID=6748|title=Speakers|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Advisors, Team Rubicon (April 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://teamrubiconusa.org/team/|title=Team Rubicon Team & Board|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Directors, [[Optiv (cybersecurity company)|Optiv Inc]] (March 2017 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Optiv Security Appoints Dave DeWalt and General (Ret.) David Petraeus to Board of Directors|url=https://www.optiv.com/about-us/press-releases/optiv-security-appoints-dave-dewalt-and-general-ret-david-petraeus-to-board-of-directors|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Co-Chairman, Global Advisory Council, Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars (August 2015 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilson Center Global Advisory Council|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/global-advisory-council|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Member, Advisory Council, Veterans Coalition for Common Sense (June 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Giffords Press Release Announcing Veterans Coalition for Common Sense|url=https://giffords.org/2016/06/veterans/|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Member, Conservation Council, [[Panthera Corporation|Panthera]] (February 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Panthera Conservation Council|url=https://www.panthera.org/conservation-council|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Senior Vice President, Royal United Services Institute (June 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rusi.org/DavidPetraeus|title=Petraeus|website=RUSI}}</ref>\n*Member, Advisory Council, Institute for the Study of War (November 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Impact%20Highlights%202017_1.pdf|title=Institute for the Study of War: 2017 Impact Highlights}}</ref>\n*Member, Advisory Council, American Corporate Partners (April 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acp-usa.org/about-us/advisory-council|title=Advisory Council|website=American Corporate Partners}}</ref>\n*Faculty Advisor, USC Student Veterans Association (September 2013 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Petraeus joins SVA as USC Chapter Advisor|url=http://studentveterans.org/media-news/172-gen-petraeus-joins-sva-as-usc-chapter-advisor|website=Student Veterans of America}}</ref>\n*Chairman, KKR Vets at Work (May 2014 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Vets @ Work|url=http://www.kkr.com/responsibility/corporate-citizenship/vets-work|website=kkr.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tamburin|first1=Adam|title=David Petraeus: Veterans are 'precious resources'|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/local/2014/11/18/david-petraeus-veterans-precious-resources/19237493/|work=Tennessean|publisher=USA Today|date=November 18, 2014}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Directors, Iraq and Afghanistan Veterans of America (IAVA) (October 2015 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iava.org/staff/|title=Staff And Board \u00bb Iraq And Afghanistan Veterans Of America (IAVA)|date=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n*Member, Concordia Leadership Council, The Concordia Summit (September 2015 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=General (Ret.) David H. Petraeus Joins Concordia Leadership Council|url=https://www.concordia.net/press/general-ret-david-h-petraeus-joins-concordia-leadership-council/|publisher=Concordia|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Trustees, The McCain Institute for International Leadership (December 2015 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sen. Joseph Lieberman and Gen David Petraeus, USA (Ret.) Join McCain Institute Board of Trustees|url=https://www.mccaininstitute.org/news/sen-joseph-lieberman-and-gen-david-petraeus-usa-ret-join-mccain-institute/|publisher=The McCain Institute for International Leadership|date=December 17, 2015}}</ref>\n*Member, Academic Advisory Board, Warrior-Scholar Project (February 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. David Petraeus, Distinguished Academics Form Board of Academic Advisors for the Warrior-Scholar Project|url=https://www.warrior-scholar.org/single-post/2016/02/17/Gen-David-Petraeus-Distinguished-Academics-Form-Board-of-Academic-Advisors-for-the-Warrior-Scholar-Project|publisher=Warrior-Scholar Project|date=February 17, 2016|access-date=March 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327144741/https://www.warrior-scholar.org/single-post/2016/02/17/Gen-David-Petraeus-Distinguished-Academics-Form-Board-of-Academic-Advisors-for-the-Warrior-Scholar-Project|archive-date=March 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Advisor, Global War on Terror Memorial Foundation (February 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwotmemorialfoundation.org/advisory-board/|title=Advisory Board}}</ref>\n*Member, National Security Advisory Council, U.S. Global Leadership Coalition (April 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usglc.org/about-us/advisory-councils/national-security-advisory-council/|title=National Security Advisory Council|website=USGLC}}</ref>\n*Trustee, Arthur F. Burns Fellowship (April 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Arthur F. Burns Fellowship Trustees|url=https://www.icfj.org/our-work/trustees|website=International Center for Journalists}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Directors, Fort Campbell Historical Foundation (September 2015 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortcampbell.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Ft.-Campbell-Historical-Foundation-990-CLIENT-COPY.pdf|title=Ft. Campbell Historical Foundation Form 990}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Advisors, The Alexander Hamilton Society (October 2016 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=AHS Welcomes General Petraeus to its Board of Advisors|url=http://www.alexanderhamiltonsociety.org/newsfeed/2016/10/17/ahs-welcomes-a-new-member-to-the-board-of-advisors|website=Alexander Hamilton Society|date=October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n*Member, Board of Advisors, Partnership for a Secure America (March 2017 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. David H. Petraeus (U.S. Army, Ret.) Joins PSA Advisory Board|url=http://www.psaonline.org/2017/03/23/gen-david-h-petraeus-ret-joins-psa-advisory-board/|website=Partnership for a Secure America|date=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*Churchill Fellow of Westminster College, Westminster College (Fulton, MO) (April 2017 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite news|title=Churchill Fellows inducted at Westminster College|url=http://www.fultonsun.com/news/local/story/2017/apr/09/churchill-fellows-inducted-westminster-college/668965/|work=Fulton Sun|date=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n*Member, Council of Advisors, Army Heritage Center Foundation (June 2017 \u2013 present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.armyheritage.org/about/board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors and Council of Advisors - Army Heritage Center Foundation|website=www.armyheritage.org}}</ref>\n*Member, Golden Plate Award Council, Academy of Achievement (October 2012 \u2013 present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Golden Plate Awards Council|url=http://www.achievement.org/our-history/awards-council/|website=Academy of Achievement}}</ref>\n\n==Recognitions and honors==\n\n===Decorations and badges===\nPetraeus's decorations and badges include the following:<ref>{{cite web|title=CIA Leadership |url=https://www.cia.gov/about-cia/leadership/david-h.-petraeus.html |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |accessdate=October 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019190931/https://www.cia.gov/about-cia/leadership/david-h.-petraeus.html |archivedate=October 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" |\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''U.S. military decorations'''\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=3|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (with 3 [[Oak Leaf Cluster]]s)\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguis