st Airborne Division Shoulder Sleeve Insignia]]\nworn as his [[Combat Service Identification Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:101st Airborne Division DUI.png|80px]]\n| 101st Airborne Division [[Distinctive Unit Insignia]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:ArmyOSB.jpg|75px]]\n|11 [[Overseas Service Bar]]s\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Foreign badges'''\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Wings badge.JPG|80px]]\n| British Army Parachutist Badge\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Brevet Parachutiste.jpg|80px]]\n| Basic French Parachutist Badge\n({{lang-fr|Brevet de Parachutisme militaire}})\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Fallschirmspringerabzeichen der Bundeswehr in Bronze.jpg|80px]]\n| [[German Parachutist Badge]] in bronze\n({{lang-de|Fallschirmspringerabzeichen}})\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:German Armed Forces Badge for Military Proficiency.jpg|80px]]\n| [[German Armed Forces Badge for Military Proficiency]] Bronze\n|}\n|}\n\n===Honorary degrees===\n* [[Eckerd College]], May 23, 2010, honorary doctorate in laws<ref>{{cite news|title =General David H. Petraeus, Commander of the United States Central Command, is Eckerd College Commencement Speaker|url=http://www.eckerd.edu/news/index.php?f=detail&id=2980|publisher=Eckerd College News and Events|date=March 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[University of Pennsylvania]], May 14, 2012, honorary doctorate of laws<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Degrees, May 2012|url=http://www.upenn.edu/commencement/event/honbio.html|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Commencement|date=May 14, 2012|access-date=May 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825134953/http://www.upenn.edu/commencement/event/honbio.html|archive-date=August 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Dickinson College]], May 20, 2012, honorary doctorate of public service<ref>{{cite web|title=CIA Director David Petraeus urges Dickinson College graduates to serve others and work through frustration|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2012/05/cia_director_david_petraeus_ur.html|work=The Patriot News (Pennlive.com)|date=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[American University of Afghanistan]], June 17, 2019, honorary doctorate of humane letters<ref>{{cite web|title=Politico New York Playbook|url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/new-york-playbook/2019/06/18/drama-grips-drivers-license-debate-nychas-new-chairman-447931?nname=new-york-playbook&nid=0000014f-1646-d88f-a1cf-5f46b74f0000&nrid=0000014e-f114-dd93-ad7f-f91520560001&nlid=630317|work=Politico|date=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Additional recognitions===\nIn 2007, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Petraeus one of the 100 most influential leaders and revolutionaries of the year as well as one of its four runners up for Time Person of the Year.<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1615513_1615454,00.html|work=Time|title=The Time 100|date=May 3, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Person of the Year 2007\">{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/personoftheyear/article/0,28804,1690753_1695388_1695379,00.html|work=Time|title=Person of the Year 2007|date=December 19, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> He was also named the second most influential American conservative by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1435461/The-most-influential-US-conservatives-1-20.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=The most influential US conservatives: 1\u201320|date=October 31, 2007|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> as well as ''The Daily Telegraph''{{'s}} 2007 Man of the Year.<ref name=\"http\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1574021/General-Petraeus-man-with-a-message-of-hope.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=General Petraeus: man with a message of hope|date=December 30, 2007|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"spiegel.de\">{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/0,1518,533781,00.html|title=US-Pr\u00e4sidentschaftswahlen: Bush geht \u2013 seine Au\u00dfenpolitik bleibt |work=Der Spiegel|date=May 27, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> In 2005, Petraeus was identified as one of America's top leaders by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref name=\"usnews.com\">{{cite web|last=Barnes |first=Julian E. |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus.htm |title=An open mind for a new Army: David Petraeus |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=May 28, 2009 |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811130943/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051031/31petraeus.htm |archivedate=August 11, 2010 |df=mdy}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a poll conducted by ''[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]'' and ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazines selected Petraeus as one of the world's top 100 public intellectuals.<ref name=\"foreignpolicy.com\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/story/cms.php?story_id=4314#bios|title=Top 100 Public Intellectuals|work=Foreign Policy |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> Also in 2008, the Static Line Association named Petraeus as its 2008 Airborne Man of the Year, and ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' named him \"America's most respected soldier\".<ref name=\"red-devils.org\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.red-devils.org/_newsletter/_pdf/documents/MayDevilsDigest.pdf|journal=Devils Digest|author=Hamill, Ken |title= Static Line Awards 2008|date=May 2008 |volume=3|number=2|publisher=508th Airborne Chapter, 82nd Airborne Division Association|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref> As 2008 came to a close, ''Newsweek'' named him the 16th most powerful person in the world in its December 20, 2008, edition,<ref name=\"newsweek.com\">{{cite news|author=Jon Meacham |url= http://www.newsweek.com/id/176300|title=The Story of Power|work=Newsweek|date=December 19, 2008|accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> and ''Prospect'' magazine named him the \"Public Intellectual of the Year\".<ref name=\"prospect-magazine.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=10558 |title=An intellectual surge |publisher=Prospect-magazine.co.uk |date=January 17, 2009 |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430112202/http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=10558 |archivedate=April 30, 2009 }}</ref> He was also named as one of the \"75 Best People in the World\" in the October 2009 issue of ''[[Esquire magazine|Esquire]]''.<ref name=\"esquire.com\">{{cite news|last= Richardson|first=John H.|url=http://www.esquire.com/features/best-people-1009|title=The 75 Best People in the World |work=[[Esquire magazine|Esquire]]|accessdate=July 4, 2010 |date=October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe OSS Society awarded Petraeus its Donovan Award May 2, 2009. In his introduction of Petraeus, Maj. Gen. John K. Singlub, USA, Ret., a 2007 award recipient and OSS Society chairman, said \"The [[William J. Donovan]] Award is given to an individual who has rendered distinguished service in the interests of the democratic process, public service, courage in all its forms and the cause of freedom.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Petraeus Receives OSS Society's Donovan Award |url=http://www.ausa.org/news/2009/Pages/PetraeusReceivesOSSSociety'sDonovanAward.aspx|date=May 13, 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128141308/http://www.ausa.org/news/2009/Pages/PetraeusReceivesOSSSociety%27sDonovanAward.aspx|archivedate=November 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Committee on American Foreign Policy]] (NCAFP) during its 35th Anniversary Gala and Award Dinner on May 28, 2009 in New York City, presented the George F. Kennan Award for Distinguished Public Service to Petraeus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prleap.com/pr/136366/|title=NCAFP 35th Anniversary Gala & Award Dinner honors General David H. Petraeus and Young Leaders in Advancing American Foreign Policy.|website=PR Leap}}</ref> The [[American Legion]] awarded its highest honor, the Distinguished Service Medal on August 25, 2009 at its 91st National Convention in Louisville, Kentucky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legion.org/convention/935/petraeus-receives-legion-service-medal|title=Petraeus receives Legion service medal|first=Steve Brooks &#124; The American|last=Legion|website=The American Legion}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2010, Petraeus received Princeton University's Madison Medal, named after the fourth president of the United States, who many{{who|date=August 2012}} consider to be Princeton's first graduate student. Established by the Association of Princeton Graduate Alumni, it is presented each year by the University to an alumnus or alumna of the Graduate School who has had a distinguished career, advanced the cause of graduate education or achieved an outstanding record of public service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2010/01/06/leach-petraeus-receive-top-alumni-awards|title=Leach, Petraeus to receive top alumni awards|website=Princeton University}}</ref> May 27, 2010, The Intrepid Sea, Air & Space Museum awarded its Freedom Award to Petraeus. \"The Intrepid Museum's mission is to honor the men and women who have served our nation. General Petraeus has led our troops overseas in that exact effort, and we are indebted to his leadership and love of country\", said Susan Marenoff, Executive Director of the Intrepid Sea, Air & Space Museum. \"This annual event throws a spotlight on individuals who have gone above and beyond the call of duty for our nation.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=General David H. Petraeus Receives Intrepid Freedom Award |url=http://www.intrepidmuseum.org/LatestNews/May-2010-(1)/General-David-H--Petraeus-Recieves-Intrepid-Salute.aspx|date=May 28, 2010}}</ref> On September 20, the American Political Science Association (APSA) presented Petraeus with its 2010 Hubert H. Humphrey Award in recognition of notable public service by a political scientist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2010-08/apsa-aps080410.php|title=American Political Science Association announces 2010 awards|website=EurekAlert!}}</ref> On December 9, 2010, [[Barbara Walters]] picked Petraeus for the Most Fascinating Person of 2010. Walters called the top commander in Afghanistan \"an American hero\".<ref name=\"Barbara Walters\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/barbara-walters-fascinating-people-2010-general-david-petraeus/story?id=12355910|title=Barbara Walters Most Fascinating People of 2010|first=A. B. C.|last=News|website=ABC News}}</ref> Petraeus was chosen as \"one of Time magazine's 50 \"People Who Mattered\" in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=12. People Who Mattered |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2036683_2036767_2036809,00.html|work=Time|date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> The same year he was named number 12 of 50 people who mattered in 2010 by the ''New Statesmen'' magazine,<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/global-issues/2010/09/general-petraeus-obama|title=50 People Who Matter 2010|work=New Statesman|date=September 21, 2010}}</ref> and Petraeus was listed as number 8 of 100 ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' Top 100 Global Thinkers for 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2010/11/29/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=0,7 |title=Foreign Policy's Second Annual List of the 100 Top Global Thinkers |work=Foreign Policy |accessdate=October 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904030659/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2010/11/29/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=0,7 |archivedate=September 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nEarly January 2011, Pete Hegseth and Wade Zirkle from Vets for Freedom, wrote an Op-Ed for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' making a claim that Petraeus should be promoted to Five-Star, which would make him [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703791904576076270514563178?mod=WSJ_Opinion_LEFTTopOpinion|work=The Wall Street Journal|first1=Pete|last1=Hegseth|first2=Wade|last2=Zirkle|title=A Fifth Star for David Petraeus|date=January 13, 2011}}</ref> In April, Petraeus was named in the 2011 ''Time'' 100.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066137,00.html|work=Time |first1=Robert|last1=Gates|date=April 21, 2011|title=The 2011 Time 100}}</ref> The Institute for the Study of War, 2011, National Security Leadership Award was presented to Petraeus on August 4, 2011. The ''[[New Statesman]]'' annual survey presents the most influential people from pop stars and dissident activists to tech gurus and heads of state, the people doing most to shape our world keep changing. September 26, 2011, Petraeus was listed as number 2 of the 50 for 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 People Who Matter in 2011|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2011/09/petraeus-general-afghanistan|work=New Statesman|date=September 26, 2011}}</ref> The Association of Special Operations Professionals named Petraeus as its 2011 Man of the Year for 2011, and was presented the award at Ft. Bragg on November 2, 2011 at its annual Special Operations Exposition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sofex.org/index.html |title=Special Operations Forces Symposium and Exposition 2011 |publisher=Sofex.org |accessdate=November 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104144459/http://sofex.org/index.html |archivedate=November 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nEarly January 2012, Petraeus was named one of \"The 50 Most Powerful People in Washington\" by ''[[GQ magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 50 Most Powerful People in Washington|url=https://www.gq.com/news-politics/politics/201202/50-most-powerful-people-in-washington-dc#slide=7|work=GQ|date=February 2012 |authors=Cherlin, Reid; Fischer, Rob; Horowitz, Jason and Zengerle, Jason}}</ref> Petraeus was inducted January 29, 2012, into the Reserve Officers Association's (ROA) Minuteman Hall of Fame as the 2011 Inductee during the 2012 ROA National Security Symposium.<ref name=roa>{{cite web |url=http://www.roa.org/site/DocServer/NSS_schedule_2012.pdf?docID=33801 |title=2012 ROA National Security Symposium, January 29 \u2013 February 1, 2012: Program |publisher=Reserve Officers Association |page=11/21 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201210905/http://www.roa.org/site/DocServer/NSS_schedule_2012.pdf?docID=33801 |archivedate=February 1, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The German Order of Merit was presented to Petraeus February 14, by the German Secretary of Defense Thomas de Maizi\u00e8re. According to de Maizi\u00e8re, he is an \"outstanding strategist and a true friend of the German people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article13870383/Verdienstkreuz-fuer-Mister-Mission-Impossible.html|title=Distinguished Service Cross for \"Mister mission Impossible\" |accessdate=February 15, 2012}}</ref> On March 16, 2012, the Dutch Minister of Defense Hans Hillen knighted Petraeus at the Hague with the [[Order of Orange-Nassau|Knight Grand Cross of the Order of Orange-Nassau]] with swords. The Minister thanked Petraeus in his speech for his, \"unconditional support to the Dutch troops and for being a driving force behind a successful mission. Through his personal efforts for cooperation between the Netherlands and America, the Netherlands could achieve significant operational successes with the Task Force Uruzgan.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=General David Petraeus Receives Royal Honor from the Netherlands|url=http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2012/03/general-petraeus.html|publisher=The Netherlands Embassy in Washington, D.C.|date=March 20, 2012|access-date=March 26, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415135039/http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2012/03/general-petraeus.html|archive-date=April 15, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Petraeus received the Golden Plate Award of the [[Academy of Achievement|American Academy of Achievement]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Golden Plate Awardees of the American Academy of Achievement |website=www.achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url= https://achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/#public-service/}}</ref>\n\nCaptured correspondence from [[Osama Bin Laden]] \"Letters from Abbottabad\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctc.usma.edu/posts/letters-from-abbottabad-bin-ladin-sidelined |title=Letters from Abbottabad: Bin Ladin Sidelined? |publisher=Combating Terrorism Center |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505212905/http://www.ctc.usma.edu/posts/letters-from-abbottabad-bin-ladin-sidelined |archive-date=May 5, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> revealed that in May 2010, Bin Laden wanted to target President [[Barack Obama]] and General Petraeus, \"The reason for concentrating on them is that Obama is the head of infidelity and killing him automatically will make Biden take over the presidency for the remainder of the term, as it is the norm over there. Biden is totally unprepared for that post, which will lead the U.S. into a crisis.\" It further went on to say, \"As for Petraeus, he is the man of the hour in this last year of the war, and killing him would alter the war's path.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Bin Laden: Kill Obama to Make Biden President| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/osama-bin-laden-letters-al-qaeda-leader-frustrated/story?id=16268578|publisher=ABC News|date=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Holly Petraeus.jpg|thumb|right|General [[George W. Casey, Jr.]] presents an award to Petraeus's wife, [[Holly Petraeus|Holly]], in 2007.]]\nThe Command and General Staff College Foundation's 2012 Distinguished Leadership Award was presented to Petraeus on May 10, 2012.<ref>{{cite press release|title=CGSC Foundation Presents Retired General David H. Petraeus with 2012 Distinguished Leadership Award|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/5/prweb9500989.htm|publisher=CGSC Foundation|date=May 11, 2012}}</ref> Petraeus was a recipient of the 2012 [[Jefferson Award for Public Service]], which was presented on June 19, 2012, at a Washington, D.C., luncheon.<ref>{{cite news|title=CIA director among winners of Jefferson Awards |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2012/06/18/3663804/cia-director-among-winners-of.html |date=June 18, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] (DAR) presented Petraeus with its Patriot Award during the 121st Continental Congress held in DAR Constitution Hall. Petraeus was the keynote speaker during Defense Night when the award was presented. The International Relations Council in Kansas City, MO, presented the Distinguished Service Award for International Statesmanship to Petraeus on September 10, 2012, in Kansas City during its 2012 Annual Awards Banquet.<ref>{{cite news|title=Join the International Relations Council for the 2012 Annual Awards Banquet|url=http://www.irckc.org/cde.cfm?event=391204|date=September 19, 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130704043322/http://www.irckc.org/cde.cfm?event=391204|archivedate=July 4, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As part of the CIA's 65th birthday, Petraeus visited the New York Stock Exchange and was invited to ring The Opening Bell to commemorate the 65th anniversary of the CIA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Central Intelligence Agency Commemorates 65th Anniversary| url=https://www.nyse.com/events/1347878253382.html|date=September 19, 2012}}</ref> The Soldiers', Sailors', Marines', Coast Guard and Airmans' Club presented Petraeus the 2012 Service to the Nation Award at its October 5 Military Ball.<ref>{{cite news|title=CIA Chief Awarded at Soldiers and Sailors Pierre Hotel Gala|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-luce/cia-chief-awarded-at-sold_b_1947668.html|date=October 17, 2012 |work=Huffington Post|first=Jim|last=Luce}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Royal United Services Institute]] (RUSI) presented Petraeus with the Chesney Gold Medal on June 10, 2013. The award marks a lifelong distinguished contribution in the defense and international security fields, to the benefit of the United Kingdom and/or the international community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chesney Gold Medal |url=http://www.rusi.org/chesneygoldmedal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513012310/http://www.rusi.org/chesneygoldmedal/|archivedate=May 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Jagello 2000 Association for Euro-Atlantic Cooperation from the Czech Republic and the Slovak Atlantic Commission awarded Petraeus the 2013 [[Czech and Slovak Transatlantic Award]] September 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=General Petraeus received the Czech and Slovak Transatlantic Awards|url=http://www.ata-sac.org/article-181-949-General-Petraeus-received-the-Czech-and-Slovak-Transatlantic-Awards|date=September 23, 2013|work=Atlantic Commission|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929183500/http://www.ata-sac.org/article-181-949-General-Petraeus-received-the-Czech-and-Slovak-Transatlantic-Awards/ |archivedate=September 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}} The award recognizes individuals who have greatly contributed to freedom and democracy in Central Europe and to strengthening of transatlantic relations</ref> The New York Historical Society awarded its 2013 History Makers Award to Petraeus on December 2, 2013, for his \"groundbreaking work in Iraq, his dynamic approach to counterinsurgency, his advocacy of a comprehensive civil-military approach, and his encouragement of strategies that resolve problems through political processes rather than violence\" according to Dr. Louise Mirrer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roger Hertog and David Petraeus to be Honored at the New-York Historical Society's Annual History Makers Gala, Monday, December 2, 2013|url=http://www.nyhistory.org/press/releases/roger-hertog-and-david-petraeus-be-honored-new-york-historical-society%E2%80%99s-annual-histo |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> On December 4, 2013, the Holland Society of New York recognized Petraeus and awarded him the Gold Medal for Outstanding Achievement in World Leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Holland Society Home Page |url=http://www.hollandsociety.com/index1.html |accessdate=December 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213125627/http://www.hollandsociety.com/index1.html |archivedate=December 13, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPetraeus was presented the West Michigan Dutch-American Leadership Award during the West Michigan's Dutch American Heritage Day, November 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. David Petraeus at Dutch-American Heritage Day |url=http://www.hollandsentinel.com/photogallery/MI/20151117/NEWS/111709997/PH/1?refresh=true |accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPetraeus was inducted into the Cornwall High School Wall of Fame, April 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Petraeus accepts Wall of Fame honor|url=http://thecornwalllocal.com/?p=5954 |accessdate=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Common Good organization presented Petraeus its American Spirit 2016 award for his leadership in conflict to safeguard the nation Friday, May 27, 2016, at its Common Good Forum & American Spirit Awards program.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Common Good Forum & American Spirit Awards|url=http://thecommongood.net/2016/04/the-common-good-forum-american-spirit-awards-with-general-david-petraeus-friday-may-27-2016-3/ |accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Association of Churchill Fellows inducted Petraeus into the Association on April 1, 2017, at Westminster College, Fulton, MO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Association of Churchill Fellows Hosts Churchill Fellows Weekend|url=https://www.nationalchurchillmuseum.org/churchillweekend.html|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> The Navy League, New York Council recognized Petraeus with its RADM J. Robert Lunney Patriot's Award during its 115th Anniversary Dinner held May 30, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York Council's 115th Anniversary Dinner Honors Military and Industry Leaders|url=https://nynavyleague.org/115th-Anniversary-Dinner|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> The International Churchill Society during their 34th International Churchill Conference presented Petreaus with the 2017 Winston S. Churchill Leadership Award, October 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Churchill Leadership Award to General David Petraeus|url=https://www.winstonchurchill.org/publications/churchill-bulletin/bulletin-112-oct-2017/churchill-leadership-award-to-general-david-Petraeus|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[The American College of Financial Services]] awarded Petraeus the Soldier Citizen Award on September 13, 2018. The award was established in 2014 to recognize extraordinary individuals who have served honorably in the United States military, have achieved success in the financial services profession and have selflessly given back to society and their community.<ref>{{cite press release|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=General David H. Petraeus Receives 2018 Soldier Citizen Award|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/general-david-h-petraeus-receives-2018-soldier-citizen-award-300715362.html|publisher=The American College of Financial Services|agency=PR Newswire|date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Petraeus received the Polish-American Centennial Award October 10, 2018 at the Mayflower Hotel in Washington DC, organized by the Polish & Slavic Federal Credit Union, Polish Supplementary School Council of America, Jozef Pilsudski Institute of America, the Kosciuszko Foundation and the Copernicus Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=BGR Group signs MPAA|url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/politico-influence/2018/10/16/bgr-group-signs-mpaa-375883|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 92nd Street Y presented Petraeus and Dr. Henry Kissinger the inaugural recipients, the Recanati-Kaplan Award for Civic Excellence and Cultural Engagement on May 19, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=92Y Gala|url=https://www.92y.org/gala/2019-recanati-kaplan-award|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> The 92nd Street Y recognized Petraeus with this inaugural award that will be presented annually to a leader whose contributions to civic dialogue and cultural engagement are of broad significance to the advancement of humanity.\n\nPetraeus' wife, [[Holly Petraeus|Holly]], has been recognized on multiple occasions for her lifelong commitment to supporting military families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dar.org/national-society/media-center/news-releases/daughters-american-revolution-convene-washington-dc-0|title=Daughters of the American Revolution Convene in Washington, D.C. 121st Continental Congress held in DAR Constitution Hall|date=March 19, 2014|website=Daughters of the American Revolution}}</ref>\n\n==Works by David Petraeus==\n\n===Speeches, public remarks, interviews, and op-eds===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* National Committee on American Foreign Policy George F. Kennan Award Acceptance Remarks. ''American Foreign Policy Interests'', 31(4) July/August 2009.\n* \"The Foreign Policy Interview with Gen. David H. Petraeus\", ''Foreign Policy'' January/February 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/story/cms.php?story_id=4587&page=3 |title=Counterinsurgency Field Manual: Afghanistan Edition \u2013 By Nathaniel C. Fick & John A. Nagl |work=Foreign Policy |date=January 5, 2009 |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106133415/http://foreignpolicy.com/story/cms.php?story_id=4587&page=3 |archivedate=January 6, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* \"Institutionalizing Change: Transformation in the US Army, 2005\u20132007\", at the May 2010 [[American Enterprise Institute]] 